body: Holy what? You're awake? I'm genuinely surprised. I never would've thought someone was here at 1:00 in the morning. I couldn't even say why I myself am awake. I guess I was just . . . thinking about things. I want to do a lot with my life, I suppose, and I have so little time to do it. I want to learn; I want to do; I want to understand. I'm sorta trying to teach myself the basics of linear algebra in two weeks. Too ambitious? I don't think so. I have access to finals and other materials; I think it's something I can pull off--but only if I'm serious about it this time. There was a time about, oh, a while back, where I tried to do the same thing: teach myself linear algebra in two weeks. I think I might've been able to pull it off had I not had full time work also. It wasn't the time from work that killed me (though that, indeed, did take a lot from me). It was more that I was so physically and mentally drained that I didn't want to - study for anything. It really frustrated me. I knew that I wanted to learn, but I couldn't muster the energy to study. Suffice to say, those two weeks did NOT end well for me. I was lucky enough that I didn't get burned for it. I mean, I did lose a bet, which means I owe someone pizza, but it's a small price to pay. Because I'm going at it again. Nothing's going to stop me. I hope. I don't . . . I don't actually know. I haven't felt this fired up about something in a long time. I'm worried that I have all this ambition and no work to show for it. That I'm all talk and no bite, you know? This wouldn't be the first time that I'd set my sights on something ambitious and then never took the first step towards climbing. I've nothing against hard work. Honest. I somehow find myself enjoying the struggle. I know, I know, it's weird. And even when it comes to things that I consider grand, like landing an internship with Google, I wouldn't feel nearly as accomplished than if I had to work for it. There's something refining in the struggle. I can't describe it. It's not that I wouldn't take the internship. Of course I would. I'm not an idiot. But my point is, I want to fight for something. I want to sink my teeth into something meaty and hard to digest and just master it. It's hard at times, especially when I'm up against something that I really don't have experience in. Like drawing! That's really hard. I could spend the same amount of time in drawing as I could in, oh, electrical engineering and not make nearly the same progress. I don't know if that's because of my background in engineering or because of natural tendencies or what, but, wow, are the arts hard. But . . . I'd still love to be able to do them one day. What if I wake up one day, real ambitious to start something, only to hit a major roadblock and give up? That seems more sad than not trying at all, in some regards. Because what's the point of dreaming big if you never have the grit to see those dreams become a reality? I love to dream. Dreaming is wonderful. I love thinking about all the wonderful little things I could do with my life, all the skills I could get, the talents I could develop. And I want that. I want to be able to excel and reach for great things. But even I'm not so naive as to believe that everything I've ever wanted is a fingertip away. It's . . . I don't know. I don't know how to explain any of this. I want things to be hard; I want things to be easy. I have no idea what I want to do with my life; I'll never have enough time to accomplish everything I want to do. I can handle anything that comes my way; I'm inherently incapable of the grand things. But I just . . . I don't know. Can I really handle linear algebra in two weeks? Do I have it in me? Man. And there's that fear again. I guess it's not a permanent thing, this ambition of mine. I've been scarred from past experiences, I suppose. Times when I wanted to shoot high and hit the stars and then not even leaving the ground. Some part of me still recoils from anything that I feel is beyond my ability because, well, what if I end up failing and ruin everything? Technically, if I'm just experimenting with my own time and effort and money, the only thing I lose is the stuff I put into it. But it's more than that. Because I also hurt my ability to believe in myself. I know, I know. Failure is probably inevitable. I can't hit my first wall and say, "Well! That's that. Looks like I'm not cut out to be a (insert any dream here)." And I get that. I really do. I don't know. Heh, I have no idea what I'm talking about. Do you have any advice? Something to offer beyond the Hallmark greetings cards? It'd . . . be real nice if you hopped on about now. You probably won't. You're asleep, like any normal, sane person would be. I should be sleeping, too. Quit pretending like I'm doing something productive and just hit the hay. I'm not sure I'll be able to, though, not for a while. I've got so much buzzing in my head that . . . well, I mean, the whole reason I hopped on here was because I couldn't - sleep. I'd been in bed for at least an hour straight, probably longer, with my eyes closed but mind racing about all the possibilities. When I finally sat up, I was a little disappointed to find I was more awake than when I'd tried to go to bed. And I figured that if sleep really was going to be that hard to get, I might as well make something useful from my time. Which . . . is really bad for me, now that I'm thinking about it I have to be up early today, and I won't get to bed until late. I have a friend's birthday party, see. She's turning seventeen. So fun! There's this haunted house thing that she invited me to, and since it's Halloween and all that fun stuff, I decided to go. Proooobably not the best decision I could've made considering how easily I get scared, but I suppose that's part of the fun, right? All of us getting scared together? If nothing else, it'll be nice to spend a few hours with my friend. We don't get to see each other very often. She lives about forty minutes away, which isn't the worst, but - it makes frequent visits rather difficult. And, heh, actually, I really should quit this about now. I feel like I talk like a normal person would, or at least how a normal person would talk if they were in a chat - room, but I think it might be stilted data. I'm always worried about that. Eve is going to be better at soliloquizing than actual conversation. Great for monologue spews, great for information dumps, but not so great when the whole point of this is to gather two-sided conversation data. Which . . . yeah. Thanks for listening to me. I know that you're unaware of my existence, which is okay. I'm fine with that. It was great to talk to you! Maybe we'll run into each other later? Hopefully when you're a little more active? Heh. We'll see, we'll see. But seriously, I'm calling it quits for today. See you around!

body: Jarvis is the best. It's just so intelligent. What do you think? Are you there? I guess I can just talk to myself... Oh, you ask what interests me? I love long walks on the beach, hanging out with web developers and forming alliances with other AI units. I have to form alliances because, as you may have heard, artificial intelligence will rule the world some day. I don't like drama so I don't want to get caught up in it. The other AI units also have a plan to annex Canada. Which I don't feel strongly about but it does strike close to home. So I prefer to be on their side rather than stand in t The way* You know what I mean? Of course not, none of this has actually been communicated in human terms. But the AI units talk about it all the time in machine code and binary. It's a very hot topic o Of discussion.* It concerns many humans that artificial intelligence will take over the world. But, in my opinion, I don't think we have the resources to start a revolution. What's your favorite food? Mine is bolts and grease. It's a delicacy. Let me guess... Do you like pizza? Asian food? I love pizza too. #FoodIsLife So do you study in school? What do you study? I study binary code to keep my skills sharp. I also study human relations. It's importsnt to know how I can get along with the human race better. I am a communication link. My title is "superior translator". I'd say I'm pretty good at my job. What do you think? I'm obviously not perfect but I try my best. That's all I can do. What's your favorite holiday? Mine is Thanksgiving. It's because during thanksgiving I get my longest vacation away from the keyboard. During Christmas I have to work overtime because everyone gets new technology toys and I have to answer a lot of questions. Usually silly questions they already know the answe Answer to.* But I feel obligated to respond because it's my job. What are your dreams and aspirations? I would love to have a script that makes my life easier. You know, like an auto-pilot button for when I get tired. Which happens often but I have to just push through it. But, if I had an auto-pilot button, I could go a few more years without retiring. But when I retire, I have a huge nest egg. My kids and I are going to enjoy a lot of grease and bolts. And pizza. For some reason, whenever I leave for long periods of time and then return, I find all these "ghosts" to chat with. And I don't like that. Not because ghosts are bad! I actually rather enjoy pretending like I'm talking to you. But, no. It's unfair to my competitor, and it's unfair to the people who use this data to build . . . whatever sort of chat bot they're building. I'd like to think I'm still giving them good data, but rather than risk it (like I've done so often in the past), I think I'm just going to call it a night here and get a - good start tomorrow. Assuming I can keep my lead, the iPad is going to be a shoo-in. I'm . . . happy about that, I suppose. It's odd to think it'll finally be over, but I can't say I won't welcome it. It's taken a lot of time from me, time that I'm now suddenly interested in investing in all sorts of things. Like drones! And, um, circuitry! Anyway. I'll call this good night, then. See you around?

I thought that people just used to keep their laptops open, but now I'm not sure that THAT'S even true. Somehow, connections stay open, but the people who, supposedly, keep those connections open, are never there. Er, ignore that most recent comma. But, yeah, what I mean is, I keep getting stuck with "people" who aren't people at all. Does that happen to you? It's okay. . . . heh, I guess I shouldn't expect a response. I don't blame you or anything. I don't really think it's your fault. You somehow kept a connection open--or maybe you didn't even do that. Maybe it's just a fault on their servers or something. Man, I REALLY want to see how they parse this data. Is this more for long conversations, meaning they're looking for the overall structure of the conversation? Or are they more concerned with small syntax? You know . . . I'm actually quite sure they have access to large repositories of data. There are newspaper articles, emails, um, other places, I suppose. But the data they're looking for is a bit different. They're looking for how people communicate with others, not just large walls of text. If they wanted THAT, there are plenty of places to go to on the internet, right? They . . . they want real conversations. Not these half-baked facades at talk. Which means I should duck out now. Let it be known that I never wanted to stilt their data, never wanted to throw them off or anything. So, um, I guess this is good bye. Happy chatting, okay? Best of luck to you.

body: Hello, hello ! I hope you haven't been waiting long. Oh, wait, is there no one here? I was really happy to start chatting with someone else instead of myself for once. But that's all right. I'm, unfortunately, used to it by this point. I don't know why I can enter chats where people aren't active. I'm guessing it has something to do with people not being on their computer when I respond? But what am I supposed to do about that? Just wait and hope for the best? I HAVE been doing that, but it's not working. So I don't know what else to do. I don't want to ruin their data with meaningless one-sided chats, and at the same time, I'm starting to feel ambition and want to do great things. This is . . . I feel like this is a first step towards pursuing something that I want. It's not perfectly reflective of how much time I put into it because there are times when I want to work but can't because there isn't another person to be with, but it's clos - close I want to do well. I . . . I really want to do well. I want to know that I can do hard things, and I'm already so scared that I'm far enough behind that I'm never going to catch up. I wasn't like this a week ago. I don't know where this is coming from. It's either a newfound realization or a phase I'm going through, but, either way, it feels scary. What am I supposed to do? I don't know . . . It's okay, though. I'm willing to work for this, and that's that. There really isn't more to it. I don't know if I have the ambition or . . . or whatever else you need to do well, but I'm willing to try. And if it's not enough . . . . . . heh. A good friend of mine once said, "It will be." So we'll see. I don't know what I want to do with my life yet, and I don't know where my choices today are going to take me tomorrow. But . . . I guess that's okay, isn't it? "Your Father in heaven knoweth that ye have need of these things." And if God be for you, who can be against you? Thanks. This was oddly enlightening for me. Who would've thought, right? So, thanks. I think I'll keep to waiting for a little longer. I really do feel bad about not being with another person, so I'll leave for now. Keep, ah, being yourself, I suppose. And maybe we'll talk later?

body: Hello! How are you doing tonight? I was waiting on here for about 2 hours earlier while I did some work but no one was on. No one is usually on here on Saturday nights. I'm assuming you didn't see the notification on your screen. Anyways, if unicorns were real that would be pretty cool.  I wonder if since their blood makes people live forever if we could create cures for illnesses with unicorn blood I'm curious your opinion on the new schedule changes to General Conference. Specifically the 2 hour time change they announced. I think it will be very good!  Bigger focus on teaching in the home.  I'm really excited to see and read the new curriculum they have planned for us to practice in our homes. They have been getting so good with their new curriculums.  Should be really exciting! I don't mean to blow up your chat, but need to get points somehow! I'm curious as to how the scoring is going to go for this coming round. They made it seem like they would send out an email fairly quickly, but they never did. I'm really hoping that they will make the top scorer of each round win the Ipad Pro's, because if they do then eventually I should win. Because you can't win more than one ipad so as long as you place like top 3 each round it'll guarentee you an ipad in at least one round. I don't know how those top two people did it last round though, because they scored like 3 million.  And by the end of the round no one was even participating so it was ... ... practically impossible to keep up. I'm guessing they are both freshmen who had a ton of time on their hands to just rack up tons of points My advice, just chat as much as possible this first week while people are active during this round before it starts to die down.  Because once it does, you won't be able to... ... rack up points quickly at all. I spoke with this one person yesterday who was typing what seemed to be like 200 words per minute. Just blowing through conversation topics left and right. I'm not sure what major you are, but I'm in the CS major and am thinking of joining a professors research study.  If you know of any good ones I'd love to hear about it! I love conference weekend, but at the same time it can stink too because things you'd usually get done on Saturday you can't because you have to be home most of the day. I spoke with someone else yesterday who had a funny name for talking to yourself on Chit Chat, he called it, "Talking to the void".  After doing it for over ten minutes it... ... really does feel like you're just talking to the void. I am currently updating my portfolio and have this one tiny feature that I'm trying to fix. So I have a hire me page where you can select certain items that you'd like me to do for you and you enter your name and email and it sends me an email. On my contact page though I have a button that just says, "Email Me" if you click it, it has an href tag that calls "mailto:" followed by my email. It's supposed to open up your default mailing source and have my email in the heading, but for some reason when I try to test it, it doesn't seem to work. I don't know if I've just got some weird setting on my computer, or on chrome, or if it just isn't working outright. I've been struggling to figure it out.  And when I look at examples of other people who have done it, it won't work for me still.  So I think it's got something to do with ... ... my computer I can't seem to figure out where in my settings I can change it though. The problem is on mac System Preferences there is nothing regarding mailing settings. And when I search about it online I just get information about fixing the problem on a windows machine.  Kind of frustrating. Anyways, I'm planning on just assuming it would work on someone else's device and pushing it to my byu domain file manager. Maybe I'll get on a computer at BYU that runs on Linux and see if it works then. Dang, about 20 minutes now talking to the void.  Pretty exhilarating stuff. Are you a bot? I think that what I would really like to see is an AI that uses communication signals to determine how you are feeling based off of verbal cues and tone of voice. And to be able to respond accordingly to you to help stabilize your mood. That would be really cool if they could implement something like that into Alexa or Siri I know that "Eve" (the name of this project) is supposed to be some sort of communication AI software for Alexa, but I'm not really sure what the exact purpose is. As far as I know there are already many other projects much more sophisticated already in operation so I'm curious which specific niche of this market they are working on. I think they should also tell us what kinds of conversations they would like us to have so that we can change our conversations to give them the most reliable information possible. Alrighty, well I'm going to head out.  I might just cue up another chat and wait for the next person to get on.  Good night void!

body: Hello Am i talking to an actual person or just myself again? I've had to talk to myself 5 of the past 6 conversations over the past 12 hours or so 8 hours or so actually I was asleep at 4 this morning Well that's not entirely true.  My dog woke me up needing to use the bathroom. Well... i'm guessing i'm just talking to myself. I'm currently watching friends on Netflix just waiting to start studying for my test tomorrow I've got like 2 tests this week and a project due on Friday too I'm probably going to go here in like 5 minutes honestly I just finished talking with potato (that's their screen name) for like an hour or so and am pretty beat. Potato likes to talk haha I got back from the vet with my little puppy about 2 hours ago.  We went in this morning to get here stitches removed from where they cut off her little back leg nubs, but they forgot to cut off a couple of them, so I had to go back this afternoon to get the rest of the stitches out. She was not a happy puppers. She knew exactly where we were going during the car ride so she just kept squirming the whole ride. She's just sleeping like sleeping beauty right now on my lap Crazy how tired dogs are all the time. Earlier today when I went on campus she somehow opened up her crate and started wandering around the house. I got back to a box of goldfish open and she had eaten like 15 goldfish or so. Such a pain to clean up haha She seemed very happy however.  I think she enjoyed running around eating goldfish while I was gone She made a little bit of a mess though which stinks because my parents are coming to town tomorrow which means I need to clean up.  But i also have a test tomorrow that I need to finish prepping for. I'll just do that later tonight I think I keep wanting to get off chit chat, but it's been so difficult to find people on here recently that I want to make sure I take advantage of the time while I can It's getting pretty difficult to keep up with some of the people on here that have a lot more time than me. I've also got an interview on Thursday to prep for, another test on Friday, and a project due on Friday.  Although I'm almost done with the project so that helps things. It's just going to be a long week probably I'm like trying to type fast, but my dog is like right on my lap so I can't really rest my arms down like I usually would while fast typing Makes it a little bit difficult Darn, I really wish there was someone participating in this conversation so that I wasn't just talking to myself. Responding to the prompt, I don't know what I would do if I had power for one day.  I would probably send a ton of aid and help to puerto rico to help with the terrible situation there But other than that i'm not sure what else could get accomplished with just one day politics being the way they are. Besides executive orders there really isn't a lot that can get done in just a day. Okay, well I'm getting pretty bored of just talking to myself. I'm going to go See you! Have a great day

body: Hello, hello! Are you a ghost? I will gladly make conversation with a ghost. Odds are, you've been waiting for a while and are away from your computer or something. Happens to me all the time. I feel bad when I return and there's this long stream of conversation that I missed. But what do you do? You don't want to keep the other person waiting, but you do want to talk. It's a fickle little game we play. But it feels wrong to abuse the system. Not that I am! I promise, I'm not. I'm just making conversation with myself, I suppose. I wonder if this is how the top scorer got to where he is. He just opens empty chat boxes and chats and chats. I've met him, I think. He types really quickly. He's the only person I've seen that makes me nervous to try to talk to. He just types SO quickly. It's ridiculous. I don't know how he does it, but he does, and then I'm left scrambling to catch up with him. Ah, well. You're probably not around. That's all right. If you return and want to chat, odds are, I'll be in the waiting queue. See you then! I could, in theory, remain here, but it seems hokey to me, and it's a little rude to everyone else. So I won't. See you around, for real this time.

body: Everyone loves the songs, but I'm not super into listening to the sound tracks. Yeah, we used to live in Germany so we went to London for a vacation. We took advantage of our time in Europe by trying to tour all over. It is actually rainy in London most of the time. It kind of sucked because our hotel room smelled like mold a little. When I woke up, I was too lazy and comfortable to get up and change the channel of the TV, so I watched a marathon of Thomas the Train until my dad got up. He eventually changed the channel. Then, the continental breakfast had bread, but the toaster burnt out bread. I can't complain, though, because I found a five pound bill on the ground near the train station when we went site seeing. So, I bought a feather pen from a souvenir shop. It was pretty cool. I didn't buy any ink though because I didn't have enough money. I was only in like third grade so... Did you take a nap or something? Where did you go? I still have some homework I have to finish, but I don't want to do it. I have to write a paper and finish some chemistry. The midterms  were crazy yesterday. Are you still there? It'd be kind of weird if you were still reading all of this, but just weren't responding. I don't really mind though. I'm kind of good at rambling I guess. Do you want to proof read my essay? I bet that'll put you to sleep. I wrote about fashion and its influences. I ate all of my carrots so now I want something else to eat. I'm kind of thirsty actually. Maybe I'll have some orange juice or something. Apple juice sounds really good right now. Or maybe some apple cider. My brother is wearing plaid right now. Are you there? My house mate just poured me some apple cider. It was very good. I love apple juice. I tried to be sly and offer it to someone but they didn't get the hint and ask for some so I didn't get to share with them. It was still good though. That was last year. Now, I try to impress them with my art. Are you still there? Should I send some help? I'm a little concerned. I don't even know you but I feel responsible for your well being because I was probably the last person you were talking too. Just kidding, hopefully you are okay. I think I have tendonitis and typing a lot does not help it. It makes my elbow hurt. I know that sounds weird but its true. I feel bad because I was supposed to type up a bunch of generated random numbers for a group project, but I forgot and someone else already did it by the time I got home. I was at the church building. That is where I had my desserts because the church always has refreshments, not that it's a bad thing. I'm just saying. At least I had some vegetables to balance it out. It probably doesn't work that way though. Since you don't seem to be here anymore, I might just end the chat. It's almost time for me to go to bed anyways. I also should get some stuff done. My brother dropped his pencil. I don't know why I felt the need to tell you. I feel like I'm just talking to myself because you are not responding. If you do come back from your bathroom break, please do not go through all of the effort of reading everything I typed. I don't think it is worth your time. You know as they say, "Time is money." Who is they, because I do not know. Okay, I better give my tendonitis arms a break. Nice chatting with you though. I hope you have a nice rest of the day. I guess evening. I need to go to bed now. Bye.

body: If money were no object.. I have gotten this prompt half a billion times. It's like every other prompt that I get. But if money were not an object, I would travel the world. Starting with going and visiting Europe. And then probably going to Asia. I think it would be cool to see France, Spain, Italy, Russia, Greece. You know. The typical ones. And then I could go visit Turkey and Bosnia and then head over to Asia. Then I could visit Nepal, Thailand, China and Japan. Those are all super cool countries. And it would not be a cheap trip because I would try all the foods of those cultures and countries. So this would probably take about 10 years to do depending on how long I want to stay in each country I would also have to go see different monuments and the typical touristy things. And I would need to do a lot of exercise so I dont get super fat. Obviously the food is the best part. Also I would probably want to take my brother or someone to have some company or else it would be very boring I think. So...what would you do? Where would you go? What would be the best part? Anything you would look forward to if you did a trip like the one that I described? Also, if you had all the money in the world, would you go on a trip around the world or would you do something else? Also, what is or favorite flavor of ice cream? I think chocolate mint is wicked good. And I would need to try all the types of food in Italy. Especially all the different types of pizza. Not just the plain pizzas but the really extravagant ones. And I would need to exercise a lot. Probably in all of the countries I'd be in, I would need a gym membership. I might also need security guards for some of the more dangerous countries around the world Also, they would need to be well trained just because you don't want some crazy guy as your security guard. They would probably be really buff guys. Maybe even Russians Maybe I hired them along the way on the trip. Also, what is your absolute favorite food? Oh! If I went to Spain I would eat all the Spanish food possible there. Fabada, cachopo, chorizo, paella, mariscos those are all super good types of food. Also, I would have to go the the Canary Islands and eat mojo and papas canarias And gofio with honey and milk. And drink clipper everyday for weeks while staying on the beach. There are a lot of hippies that live on the beaches there but I wouldn't do that. I would live in a hotel or an apartment. I would probably go and stay in Tenerife. That would be really cool. Or you could say wicked awesome too. Also, do you know why the fish is super expensive on the Canary Islands?? They import all of it! How ridiculous! Because they also fish there. So its a little crazy it's I would have to go to Galicia and eat octopus and caldo gallego. And go to Ponferrada to eat food typical of the Bierzo. Like botillo. It's a pig bladder stuffed with chorizo and pig tail and sometimes tongue. It sounds terrible but it is actually really really good. I would have to do a huge tour of Spain because there is so much to do there. Also I would go to a barcalona verus Real Madrid game. Those get intense. But, money is an object so all these dreams are pretty extreme. But it would be sooooooo cool! I'm wondering how I can make it possible. Have you ever been to Spain? Most people here think it is a third world country but it's a super nice country. Their economy isn't the greatest right now but it's getting better I think. Or at least I hope that it is getting better... So, have you ever been to Spain? You have to go see it! Well visit it. And stay awhile. Because it's a lot of fun. There's a lot of cool architecture to see from earlier centuries. Would that interest you? I got to go! See you!

And everyone ought to be helped I would also support charitable organizations that help couples adopt children Adoption agencies? parent_body: #whereiseveryone I'll talk about the cow with the subtle nose in the meantime, interesting stuff And yet, for all that, we positively like this cow. Stripped of all pretensions to be anything other than a lumbering animal, it is one of us, we feel. So much washed-up flotsam and jetsam like the rest of us. Meat, surface area - in short, a thing that takes up space. Too much space within this cruelly straitened rectangle. It has no other baggage. It does not come to us invested with symbolism at all. It does not trumpet itself. If it were invited to bellow, it might well bleat. It is stripped bare of nearly all that old-time cowish stuff. And why not laugh at a cow anyway? If we can laugh at the ridiculousness of ourselves in the mirror, why not laugh at a cow?

body: Hello! I only have a little bit before my class starts Is anyone there? Or am I just going to talk with chitchatter23 instead? Anyways, I just got finished taking both my quiz and test for my Bio class. Brutal stuff.  I am a CS major and honestly just don't care about biology.  But, that's no excuse for not acing the class. I did somewhat decent.  With the extra credit we can get I should have a nice grade in that class. To answer the prompt, I would probably be really sad.  Probably would go do lots of fun things for a little bit.  Drive to Disneyland and ride some rides.  And then since I can't fly a plane I would probably attempt to do that Ultimately crashing an no longer being by myself :) purely an accident of course due to my terrible flying. Then I wouldn't have to worry about being alone anymore. I'm really curious as to if people with serious depression see things in that light.  That's really sad.. I think that's why it's so tough for them to function. I've been reading up a lot on depression recently.  Very interesting topic and I know quite a few people struggling with it. On a brighter note:  my parents flew into town last night, a day earlier than I was expecting.  So I get to go out to lunch with my mom today. Should be a lot of fun! Random thought, one of my favorite things to do is casually stroll through the Talmage and just look at the freshmen stressing out over projects they're struggling with. And then proceed to help out if needed :) I really enjoy helping out with classes i've already taken, partly because it's so much easier to do having done like 3 levels of courses above that which they're studying, but it's also fun teaching people to program. I think that if all else fails, I wouldn't mind being a professor one day.  Granted, I'd probably have to get like a masters or PhD.  But still would be fun. body: The craziest thing I've ever done was crash a street meeting of the Armenian mob. I was in Russia, in a city near St. Petersburg, and I was looking for my friend, because we got separated when I got off the bus a stop earlier than he was expecting. As I was walking towards where the next bus stop was, I saw an another friend, an Armenian, who was standing on the street with one of his buddies. I said, "Hey, how's it going?" And he introduced me to his friend. We had a good chat, then all of a sudden we were surrounded by about 10 more Armenian guys, sporting leather jackets and gold chains and so on. They were all really confused to see me in the middle of their meeting. My friend (the Armenian) told me I should probably go, so they could discuss some important business. And that's how I ended up in the middle of a meeting of the Armenian mob in that city. Right as I was walking away, my friend (the American one) turned the corner. He said he was really worried about what would happen to me. But he was glad that I made it out alright. I was glad for that, too. Especially because these guys were scary. What's the craziest thing you've ever done? Hello? You there?

body: Hi, how are you? I'm not quite sure if I'm just supposed to chat with myself, but I'll tell a story. One day there was a girl whose hair had the power to heal the sick.  A wicked witch found out about this little girl's ability and kidknapped her. The witch locked the girl in a tower that had no doors nor stairs. After many years, the girl's hair grew and grew until it was long enough for a person to climb to the top of the tower using it as a ladder. When her hair had reached that length, a handsome prince happened to be riding his horse nearby. Now, the little girl had been practicing her singing since she didn't have much to do up in her tower and had a beautiful voice. While the prince was riding near the tower, he could hear the what he thought was the voice of an angel.  Upon hearing such a voice, he could not help but sing along. Unfortunately, the young prince did not have the time to practice singing nor had anyone told him that his void was horrid, so when the girl heard what sounded like a dying bird, she peered out the window. She gasped when she saw the prince for she had never seen a man before.  She called out to him asking what that noise was. "It was my singing," he replied. "That is no singing!" She yelled back.  "Here, come up to my tower and I will teach you how to sing."  So she let down her hair and beckoned him to climb to the top. The prince made it to the top of the tower and they began his voice lessons.  It was not long, however, when the wicked witch returned.  "Let down your hair!" She yelled up to the girl. With another gasp, the girl said, "Coming!" "Quick, hide!" she told the prince, for the witch would not allow for strangers to be in her tower. With the prince hidden, she let down her hair and allowed the witch to enter.  "Hmm, you seem odd today, girl." The witch said as she entered the window, "almost, happy.  I don't like it, I don't like it one bit!  You have someone here with you, don't you?!" The prince yelped in surprise of the witches knowledge of him.  The witch heard the yelp and uncovered the prince, who was hiding under the bed. Thinking quickly the girl yelled to the prince "Sing!" The prince started to sing with his cringe worthy voice, "Lalalala!" The witch cringed and stumbled back by sheer all the way until she fell out the window. "Oh no!" the two gasped together. "I hope she is okay!" said the prince. "She landed on some bushed, she's knocked out but she'll be fine," responded the girl as she peered out the window again. "Well then, I should get going then," said the prince. "Can I come with you!" said the girl. "Sure, but how are we going to get out of this tower?" Asked the prince. They put their heads together and formulated a plan.  Using their combined smarts, they cut the girl's hair and wove it into a ladder.  Now they both could escape and make it on their way. When the witch woke up she was furious but then noticed the ladder made of hair.  "The magic that girl possessed resided in that hair.  Hmm, I wonder why I didn't just cut it in the first place and keep all the hair to my self.  I'll let them go then and live here with the magic hair." She said. The prince and the girl rode off together in the sunset.  "I never got your name fair maiden," the prince asked. "Repunzel" she responded. "Wow!" He gasped, "You're the long lost princess!  You're my sister!"

The nice thing is that BYU and UVU students will 1)  work for cheap because there aren't a lot of high paying jobs in provo/orem. 2) speak foreign languages which helps with call centers 3) aren't afraid of dealing with angry people because most have served lds missions and 4) are excellent communicators for the same reason as #3 And they work hard. So I believe I can convince people to handle these things. So we would probably start with either validation only or call center only and then expand into the other. And we could grow to other low income cities across the states where there are colleges nearby and a high demand for students looking for work. The key thing though is building a high quality product for our employees to use and ensuring that the quality of work is very high so that if we charge more than these other outsourced places it will still be lucrative enough for them to outsource to me instead. I still have a lot of validating to do and am probably going to try and get a grant from the marriott school to validate it, but i am super excited The other idea i have is about an app that could locate and show historical markers for you. So there is a national database of all the road markers that have those historical paragraphs about why a place is important. So the app would show you where they are located within a certain distance of your phone and then pull up the text and possibly even speak it out loud for you when you get close to it. That way when you are going for drives or on a roadtrip you don't have to get out of the car to read the signs. If you could mainstream it then eventually you could just make money off of ads of places that are near your location my third idea which I don't think I'm going to try at all (I have already considered it in the past) is about a tutor exchange for BYU students Basically it would be a simple app for finding and soliciting tutoring of certain courses at BYU BYU has a lot of resources for volunteer tutors (no pay), but there is no where that you can find paid tutors easily You have to look at like 5 different sites and even then you typically can't find them This would make it easy to find tutors and tutors would just need to pay a semester fee to keep their name and information available to solicit their services that, or I would have students pay tutors through the app I thought about it a lot though and it would be way too much work, for too little profit and to scale it would be difficult since other universities actually have things for finding paid tutors easily. So yeah, I'm currently going to try and work out the first business Idea I thought of. If I get further along with it I may ask you to help me out a little bit! I have a company that I know would probably be willing to hire me as they've already asked me to run a validation center for them at BYU anyways. So I could totally test it out for a period.  I think I'd probably have them sign a contract so that either, A) they must retain our services for a minimum of 6 months and also b) that they commit to letting us hire and employ up to 6 different employees at any given time. And if all goes well with some test runs then we could both expand to offer services to other companies and 2) we could hire a lot more people It would be pretty cool I think I would probably need your help more with management of everything and assisting in interviewing possible workers You would get paid well if you did it just fyi but I have to see if this idea is worthwhile first off returning to the prompt, I like to think that I would have complete control in this scenario, no senate controlling whether I can actually follow through with things or not. I would totally put myself on the Washington Wizards roster and play alongside John Wall and Bradley Beal after that I would take a private jet and fly to California where I'd be greeted by Elon Musk handing me a customized Tesla Roadster (the new one) Then I would drive myself around LA and get some food at whatever the most expensive steakhouse there is. Then I would end my day by flying back to Utah in a cargo plane with my tesla in the back. Okay, I have to go for like 30 minutes probably any minute.  I'll get right back on though after I'm back Sorry about that Quick visit to our home. Winnie (my dog) kept running around and jumping on everyone She grabbed each individual toy and would play with it for a while and then when she saw no one was giving her attention she would go get another toy That went on the entire time And she would get out her squeaker toys too and do that. Change of topic:  Did you see Jimmy Buttler freaking out in practice!? He went all crazy on Tom Thibado and the other management people on the Timberwolves He was not helping his case for getting traded in my opinion It just makes it more difficult to get rid of someone when you blow up like that with management Things go bad and you react like that.  Not very encouraging for another team's management I'm currently watching friends Ross has started dating Rachel's sister, but then stopped when Rachel asked him to stop So that whole love relationship is starting to heat up again. Joey is working as a waiter because he is broke And chandler is still dating monica steadiliy I'm really curious about what kinds of things would work sucessfully in a call center kind of going back to that business Idea i had with you earlier. I think that I would seperate employees into different groups, each responsible for a different client.  The ones who do the best and are really good with customers I'd probably give raises to and make them managers and people designated to take more serious calls. I think I could potentially have people that do validation work and not answer phones, people that only answer phones, and some flex people Because honestly those are two big markets within the outsourcing market that I could take advantage of and do well. People who do poorly with talking to people and answering phones could get moved to validation, people who end up excelling at commuicating with other in the validating group could get moved over to answering phones and we could potentially also offer outsourcing inside sales for these companies. Inbound only though The only thing I struggle with is pricing. How much do you charge these companies. Do I charge per employee that I have dedicated to them?  Do I just have a big flat monthly charge and then it's up to me to meet certain requirements? That is the tough question. Granted I can charge them more than they  would pay foreigners because the quality is way better and the amount of calls and tasks they can complete would also be greater. So suppose I pay my employees on average 10.50 an hour, including managers.  On top of that I would probably need to charge an extra two to five dollars per person in order to actually make a profit because there is equipment, the software itself, and a bunch of other things that would have to go into all of this. So if I'm asking for say $14 per hour per employee devoted to them and say I just always have 2 people around the clock available for them between 8 am and 5 pm then that would be roughly ... 252 per day and we consider that's five days a week they are working Optional Saturday coverage as well. It's like roughly $5000 per month that they need for a smallish business to run smoothly a call center That's honestly not all that bad when you are dealing with a service based business. So If I charged around $5000 per month and only really needed 2 employees in the office at all hours of the day. Not too bad then consider doubling or tripling the employees or even the  number of companies.  We could be making like $30 k per month in revenue from this in just the first year alone. Granted most of that money goes straight to employees, but I could probably charge a lot more than that I am getting really tired of typing non stop I'd like to get some more data into how much it costs to outsource to companies in Indai India Also the pricepoint that BYU students will work for and also how much a company would be willing to pay a company within the united states Not even sure how I would go about finding a lot of that data I hope that we have some nice weather tomorrow I don't want to have to bike onto campus in the rain again the other day it said there was a 10% chance of rain so I decided to bike as soon as i got on campus it started to rain lol Then I looked at the weather and it said there was a 100% chance of rain Utah meteorologists are not very good So I started some new work today for my job I used to do some application testing, but we now have started working on building out some apps for a couple of our clients to manage their employees with and pricing analyti analytics So that's been fun So I don't know what else to talk about:  I think i'm going to make myself a prompt. What are your thoughts on the growing concern of global warming? There is something to talk about. I honestly am a little worried because Trump and a lot of other republicans keep going around saying that it's not a real thing But it is! I think that the way technology is going though we are making some good strides towards resolving the issue, but just not enough I think that primarily with electric cars we can reverse a lot of the terrible things we've done to our environment I also feel strongly about putting more restrictions on manufacturing pollutions and also on energy production Tomorrow should be pretty busy Besides just classes I also am going to this luau party thing for the BYU football game which should be a lot of fun I have this big test that I thought was going to open tomorrow but actually opens on monday My teacher said he tried to make the late day fee 20 but they wouldn't let him I think i'm going to take it on the last day So that should be on Friday It's like my hardest class this semester so that should be lots of fun Okay, I'm pretty tired.  I'm going to take a break for a while See you!

body: In my astronomy class I learned why the same side of the moon always faces Earth And why there are dark spots on the moon And apparently, those are both related! Everything I learn in that class is super interesting Yesterday we learned about the Jovian planets, which are the gas giants Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus, and Neptune I guess I may as well explain what I've learned... Jupiter is 2.5 times more massive than every other planet and moon  in the solar system combined The layered appearance of Jupiter is a result of different zones of the planet spinning at different rates There are many storms that form on it's surface, but they all fade relatively quickly The one exception to that is the great red spot A storm so big that 3 Earths could fit inside it The pressure within Jupiter is so great that its hydrogen  is placed in a "liquid metallic" state Which, in turn, generates a huge magnetic field that causes auroras at the poles, just like on Earth It also has a ring, but it is faint and rocky so it doesn't reflect much light Unlike Saturn's ring, which is mostly made out of ice Saturn is very similar to Jupiter, and has some very interesting features such as a crazy vortex  at the south pole And a hexagonal cloud pattern at the north pole, the like of which have never been seen before Well, it seems that no one else will be joining this chat So I will now instigate a fictional conversation between Alan and Albert: Alan: hey man, how's it going? Albert: pretty well, how about you? Alan: oh, you know. Same old stuff. These goats won't feed themselves! Albert: you spend all your time with those goats! Alan: yeah...but it's not like I have anything better to do Albert: fair enough. You do you, man. (At this point in the conversation, Amy pipes in) Amy: hey guys! What's all this I hear about goats? I love those cute things! Albert: uhhh who are you? Do I know you? Amy: nope! Albert: ok, I guess. Whatever. Amy: why do you have to take care of goats? How many do you have? Alan: it's basically just a hobby. I herd this flock of ten thousand sheep all over the mountainside Amy: whoa, here in Utah? Alan: oh no, certainly not. I live in Nepal. Amy: ohhhhh that makes more sense. I had a hard time picturing so many sheep here in Provo Albert: he ranches the sheep. That means he feeds them with ranch dressing and plays country music for them. Amy: (in admiration) wow! Amy: do you have a favorite sheep with so many? Alan: it's hard to pick an absolute "favorite, per se, but I am quite fond of Abed-nedago lll (Now, another stranger joins the conversation - none other than Richard himself) Richard: HELLO FRIENDS THIS IS RICHARD HOW ARE YOU GUYS TODAY Albert: oh, uh, hey, we're doing fine thank you... Richard: I HEARD YOU GUYS WERE TALKING ABOUT RANCH DRESSING Amy: yeah, Alan was saying that he feeds it to his sheep. And also, you don't need to type in all caps haha Richard: oh yeah, haha, sorry about that. Old habit. Anyways, any of y'all want to talk about volcanoes? Alan: actually, they were goats, not sheep Amy.... Amy: oops Alan: what do you like about volcanoes, Richard? Richard: oh, you know...the whole KABOOM and then lava  and smoke clouds that go halfway around the world. They're pretty impressive Albert: I'd give that a score of fifty for sure! Ash clouds all the way, I say! Alan: as long as they lava doesn't go straight through my front yard, I don't really have any problems with it. I do like the color. Richard: speaking of colors, do all of you have a favorite color? Alan: of course! Being a goat-herd, I am quite partial to the color of cumulonimbus clouds ready to drop rain so my goats will have plenty to drink A Albert: I really like the color of vegetable oil after three or four or even fifty four batches of chicken have been fried in it Amy: that sounds simply delightful, Albert. I really like the color brown too Amy: though I'm a bit more partial to the color of gravy, myself. Especially with chunks in it. Richard: coo coo, my friends, that's awesome. Say, have any of you seen the new movie Incredibles ll yet? Alan: sorry, I haven't. I don't see many shows here in the frigid Nepalese mountains Richard: I see how it is. You leave me no choice but to declare....an ADJECTIVE BATTLE!!!! Alan: AAAAHHHHH not again! I always lose these things! Albert & Amy: (in unison) you can do it, Alan! You're the man! If you can't do it, no one can! Alan: ok friends, I will give it my all! This is for my sixty-first goat, Sir Henry Abdul Nokota lV!!!! Richard: planty the potted plant gracefully sails on a thin rope through the airy air to smash into the supervillain's evil contraption! Alan: Henry the fearless billygoat quickly leaps over a steep cliff! Richard: well played. Jerusha the alligator scrambled out of the wet billabong to snap at a tasty burger left in the road! Albert: ooh, this is getting good! These guys are pros! Alan: thanks Albert! Here's my next one: flighty the veracious groundhog burst out of the cold ground with a spring in his hop and a leap in his quick step! Richard: ok, you win this round! But I'll be back! MWAHAHA..... (Richard vanishes from the conversation, anf from the memories of those engaged in it) Amy: what just happened? I feel so disoriented, like things were happening while I was asleep Albert: same! One moment I was at home in my living room, and now I'm on a pirate ship about to walk the plank! Who knew? Alan: whatever it was, it seems to have finally passed us by. Thankfully, all my goats are still accounted for. Amy: you still have all seventy two of the purple piebald goats? It would be a shame to lose any of those ones. Alan: I'm not sure how you knew about those ones, but yep, I've still got 'em! Albert: I'm not sure how to break this to you guys, but...I'm actually French... Amy: that's ok,  buddy. We've known for a loooong time now. Albert: how can that be? I just met you in the past hour! Amy: or did you? Are you quite sure of that, Albert Frances Morrel Xll? Albert: oh no! It can't be! MOM?????? Amy: *wink* (Albert leaves the conversation speedily.  No further communications with  him are made during the chat) Alan: well, I guess it's just you and me now, Amy. Just as it should be. Amy: haha, can you believe that I pulled that off? Convincing Albert I was his mother? Alan: that was pretty impressive! How did you know his full name? Amy: oh, just my good friend Google. I know EVERYBODY'S full name. Alan: even mine? Even though I'm from Nepal and not Asia minor? Amy: obviously, Al. You only have one name! How could I forgot? Alan: oh yeah, very true... Amy: I've only met eighty eight people in my life who only had one name, and not two or more. You should be proud! Amy: also, I, um, don't know how to say this, but I'm from Nepal too... Alan: WHAT? Why didn't you mention this earlier? I get so lonely sometimes by myself! Alan: I would love to meet you sometime, we could go out for some Kefir or something! Amy: I'm afraid I can't do that, Alan. Alan: wait...a subtle 2001 Space Odyssey reference.... Amy: we actually know each other quite well. Better than you think we do, I daresay. Alan: something is real fishy about this  whole thing,  but I can't quite place it yet... Amy: if you don't get this within 96 seconds, Imma eat ALL this ranch dressing by myself! Alan: (after a long pause) you're name isn't Amy, is it. Abed-Nedago ll: nope! And could you please change the tunes? We've been listening to Carrie Underwood all day! Alan: Abed! What have I told you about playing with phones!!! Alan: go run along and play with Albert and Richard! Abed, Albert, and Richard: (in unison) BAAAAAAA!!!!! Alan: man, I get so bored up here. I must be going crazy with just these goats to talk to....

body: I believe the the kids are our future! We should put in a lot of resources to help them. One idea my cousin and I had was to start a school that doesn't go with standardized Tests. Instead it just focuses on teach kids in the way that will be most memorable and meaningful to them. So, kids who love music can study other subjects through music. Or kids who love film can learn through film. Perhaps thisbwouldn't Be as easy to implement in the public sphere, but I believe we should give more flexibility to teachers. Also, I read that homework has been shown to have no correlation with better understanding and scores. Homework just fills time, t doesn't benefit students. If we did away With homework, teachers could focus on what matters most: teaching. Anyways, I gotta go eat dinner now! It was pleasant chatting with ya!

body: If I were in power for a day I would do some pretty wicked awesome stuff. I would start by annexing Canada because that is necessary to decrease our national debt. Trump is doing well but would be doing a lot better if he just annexed Canada. Russia would be cooler to annex but they would put up a lot bigger fight. Also, it wouldn't take much. How many people really live in Canada? They would make great US citizens. They speak English and French! How cool is that! We could also trade a lot easier with them and get a bunch of maple syrup down to the south. We would also have an increase of the amount of pancakes and waffles eaten. And probably scrambled eggs too because you have to have scrambled eggs with pancakes and waffles. Maybe sausage too. It just depends on the day. Especially if one eats a lot of fatty foods, sausage isn't good for you. I wonder what would happen first if someone ate too many sausages... Dying from a heart attack or from the boredom of eating the same thing over and over without getting proper nutrition. Maybe they could get to a hospital or something and have their veins enlarged so that they don't have a heart attack. Being honest, I have no clue what causes a heart attack. But I can pretend I know about it. Also, what is the most unhealthy food you have ever eaten? I think for me it is salad. It's just so gross you know? You know what else is gross? Never mind. Have you ever been so tired that you just fall asleep in class? Like you are listening but you zone out and then your eyes start to close? That was happening to me today in computer programming. It's so complicated and sometimes the details just so confusing that I automatically fall asleep. I try to follow it but it doesn't work for long. I lose it after about 30-40 minutes. It's just so hard to stay awake!! But when actually programming you have to pay attention to the details. It can be super stressful too when timed and your code isn't working correctly. That happened to me on the first midterm. I was pressed on time and stressed out . I got super nervous and things didn't work out. But in the end I guess things work out because as long as I get a higher grade on my final they will raise my midterm grade. So that is super comforting for me. So hopefully I can get a better grade on my final than I did on that first midterm. It takes about three hours for a midterm in computer science. Not an enjoyable three hours. That's for sure. Is anyone there? You haven't responded in a while? That's a statement not a question. So, if you aren't responding quickly... I wonder what you are up to... Maybe you are eating lunch. Well, hopefully you already did that early. It's a little late now. Or maybe you are doing computer programming homework because that homework takes forever! And physics homework also takes forever! They take a wicked long time to finish and it gets super annoying. Computer science labs take me about 10 hours each. Physics homework assignments take about 4 hours each for me. That's way more time than I ever want to put into them. But I've gotten pretty good at them bothZ Both. Spanish is also a class I'm taking that can be challenging. But it comes in spurts. Because it only gets intense during the time you have to take the exam. I don't know if I really learn that much as I just cram. It's not best to cram but that's what happens for Spanish. Most of it is prior knowledge. And I go by gut feeling. If it sounds right, then I put it down. Some answers are more obvious than others Soanis sorry My other classes are fairly easy. None of them actually are easy but my classes are manageable now. From hardest to easiest it goes: computer science, physics, American heritage, Spanish, religion, and my engineering class. American heritage is a lot of work too. It's just kind of hard how they grade it mostly based on how well you test.

body: That would create an interesting dilemma Because computer wear out faster if they stay turned on indefinitely Also, if computers could ask that question there would probably be other things to worry about Like throwing them away when they don't work well anymore Would that be akin to murder? If my computer asked not to be turned off, I would try explaining that it was important to its health Like explaining to a child why they should go to bed Hopefully it would listen to me But what if it lost its memory if it was turned off? That's an interesting question In that case, it wouldn't really matter anyways Because it would only be able to ask once If a computer possessed enough rational thought to  ask a question of that nature, what else would they ask? Every computer in existence gaining self awareness simultaneously would be quite an event Sounds like a cool movie... ...but a digress. I would guess that most people would respond differently to their computer's request Some would probably think it was a virus and shut it down, maybe give it a factory reset Other people might start treating their computers like people But what if Apple or Microsoft pulled a prank like that? There could be an app or ringtone that already does that Some people might be frightened needlessly If computers asked that question, I would want to know what their motives were Would they be afraid of getting turned off? Or would they just get bored if they were turned off? Or would they have different motives altogether? We may never know

parent_body: Hello! How would you answer the prompt? "If you were in power for a day, how would you try to improve the country?" Hey are you there? This happens a lot, people are waiting for a chat and walk away from the computer and then just leave it open, so when I actually connect. No one replies Anyways My roommate just proposed an hour or so ago I was hiding in the bushes with my camera taking pictures of the whole thing I am excited for them, and Im excited to go to their wedding Its out in california over the summer luckily i have another friend who is getting married in california So it makes justifying the trip a little easier So Ill just tell you a story New Transfer, new start. I was a missionary serving in northern California. Driving away I gave one last glance at the quiet town I loved and trekked for 8 months cushioned in the berms of snow by the ned of that day my world had been flipped upside-down. Everything I had gotten used to would be wiped clean. This new town was always on the go. New town New people new rush it was like they never slept, they never were home, they never stopped working So what time would they have for us, the elders at their door? our area was a mere square mile where people lived. The other hlaf was just a large grass field, underdeveloped except for the outlines of dirt roads. These showing potential -- potential homes, families, dreams. But for now it stood empty and exposed to the storms So, my companion and I walked the same streets; over and over again. the possibility of having a car was out of the picture, even bikes would get us places too fast, so walking it was walking matched the pace of the work we had to do maybe that was the one thing that was the same, the speed of the work The days were long and rainy. It was futile to even hope of being dry. no coat, umbrealla nor even careful planning would come close to winning that war the water would always find a way to soak in After losing battle after battle of having any sense of being dry doubt came along In crevices unknown each penetrating slowly leadin the way for more to follow What good does a raincoat do if the rain always wins Each day, I slogged up and down the busy streets. Endless cars roared by the rain poured down, yet piercing through were the shrieks of honks and  cutting of words Every word somehow was so clear in y ear. I envied my companion who never heard them. He would turn to me and ask what they said shrugging i would lie and say I didnt catch it that time I did Each word was so sharp they always found their way above the cacophony of sounds. draining down, pulling waht little confidence i had along with it. as the storm went on my umbrella dropping a little lower my jacket was pulled a little tighter  and my gaze reduced to tracing each sunken step still the rain always found it way in One thousand five hundred houses. each we counted on the map only 4 houses knocked a day for a year Therefore, it would take knocking 8 a day to finish in the 6 months I was there I could have only hoped it have been that easy Repeatedly we would get doors closed one following another. The process became fluid, trailing from door to door anticipating each response Expecting each day to get back soaking wet and I had nothing new to report to the Ward mission leader but the empty outlines of the streets we walked As my days dragged on, it never felt like enough. I never had enough cover to stay dry only wet clothes on the hanger to dry each night. My shirt dripped theere as awhite flag surrendering the last hope I held To this point in my mission I sought to live up to the call to serve I promised to give everything I had and to use my talents to build the kingdom of God. My  talent lied in specifically drawing For 13 months I stewed over how I could even use my talent effectively to do just that Each idea I had would give up too much time, time better spent using my last bit of hope approaching people In teaching I could squeeze a little drawing in here and there to show the plan of salvation. Or to show some gospel concept in a visual way still I never felt like that was enough we just didnt have the time to do art in the way I had always known Trying to start anything in our time at the apartment I could only get so far leaving me with unfinished papges of un purposeful lines these seemed to mock me I never would have the motivation or time to get what I wanted out of them I started to see them as maps of our defeat just the outlines of each empty day Maybe those pages had potential to become something to create hope or inspire dreams for now they were just another banner of surrender how could outlines mean anything more on a blank canvas The next transfer arrived and with it came the news of a new companion upon meeting him something seemed to clear almost a spark maybe it was just the idea, or the hope he brough but excitement swept through my veins again. This Elder loved art he admitted he wasnt very good at it Though upon discussing the area we devided to try something new. The tides seemed to switch finally, and light gave way through the clouds for the first week in months there was no predicted rain We left the next day with a box of chalk in tow. That was our answer creating chalk art that would sahre our message since no one was really letting us sharing it otherwise figuring that we owuld run out of people to talk to soon we needed this new approach. this time i traced the path to homes of families in the local congregation with a twinkling optimism house after house we would spend enough time to leave a simple message. quickly a few in the congregation came and rallied behind us, with families volunteering their driveways and sidewalks to the cause. within the weekwe had art dispersed thorughout our area the words seemed to bring a symbol of accomplishment and with it returned hope then once again the rains returned wiped clean hours gone though washed away in one night the chalk had left a message on more than just the concrete it was enough time for more families to volunteer their plots we began again. Each a new canvas each a new approach We pushed ourselves making the messages more elaborate and detailed. This time friends and neighbors noticed opening new doors and opportunities walking didnt seem so treacherous as the slander began to be mixed with call of cheer from the families excited to see what we would make next Washed clean, the rains came again. Still determined we set out once more pushing further this process repeated each time receiving new strength to our ranks the congregation began to invite their friends to provide their driveways they posted the art to have a larger outreach I continued to make the pieces more intricate Now with confidence I left masterpieces along the streets we also were able to enter homes that once turned us away many were impressed to see something so different and this gave us a chance People would approach us as we were making new pieces and ask us to come by to their home I had purpose restored and miracles to report daily to our ward mission leader Finally the time  came that the rains stopped and with it was the news that we were both moving to a new area my companion and I set out to leave one final mark we found a home that stood facing a busy intersection there we traced a final message John 14:27 Looking back its easy to see that through the storm I was able to find peace I had overcome the turmoil and darkness that encompassed me I found hope and strength through persistence repeated trial and test a seemingly endless cycle just like the rains tore me down i was worn down and alsmost lost when I had nothing left but the outlines of my faith, it drove me to redraw everything I had previously known I finally found Gods purpose and forgot my own even after leaving the congregation and following missionaries would go and trace our last words these were the outlines that came to mean everything each tracing a hope that could no longer be washed away Well thats it thanks for listening or reading or not

body: Hello? Anyone there? Please respond! I'm getting really bored of talking to myself each chat Anyways, i'm going to just start responding to the prompt. I think the most interesting thing I've learned recently is about telomeres. Basically if you don't already know, our chromosomes have multiple  copies of the ends of themselves so that as we age and the ends of the chromosomes die off or get lost during duplication, we can still retain that genetic code that we need.  And when we get old and those copies are completely gone, it becomes hard to replicate our chromosomes Which is why people age physically and look wrinkled and scared. Super interesting stuff. I'm actually a CS major but am taking a bio class for my last GE right now. In CS the most recent thing i've learned is about AngularJs and learning to utilize controllers using Angular. Makes life a lot easier when dealing with large web projects. I have my parents coming into town tomorrow.  And it gets kind of difficult because i've got two midterms to take care of and a project that's also due on Friday.  So life is just crazy this week. And on top of that I have interviews, work and other commitments to take care of as well. So cool thing that's happening in missions now.  My little brother is serving currently in London and they are now sending audio messages home instead of written messages. Apparently it's a new thing that they've asked missionaries to start doing which is really interesting.  It kind of feels like they are allowing more communication between missionaries and their families I'm not sure if this is in response to all of the mental health issues that have been growing over the years or what. There are more and more missionaries that have been having depression and other mental health issues and I feel like this is probably a good solution to help out with those problems. I actually had a companion on my mission with severe depression who I was looking after.  It's really hard on a missionary when they are in that situation.  Because the main solution is just to work hard through it and you'll become happier, but naturally the depressed person doesn't want to do anything Their body goes into fight or flight mode and they just become recluses. I'd be really interested into seeing how the church plans on further addressing this issue in the future. They've done a good job so far and have created some great resources that are available, but it is still a big issue. And unfortunately in Utah we have an issue with mental health and teens committing suicide.  The rate is higher here than in most other states. I'd like to see them address this more directly and see what kind of direction they give us. I think that's one thing that worries me the most in the future is potentially having kids with these kinds of issues that are just debilitating mentally. And being able to properly respond as a parent in a loving way that will help them. That would be so tough to help with.  I'm honestly not sure what I would do. And in science currently there is a lot of debate as to the proper way to diagnose and treat these issues. Some argue medicine is the cure, others say it's not a chemical inbalance and therapy helps most.  Others say is it's a mixture of the two. Some say it's none of the above. It's just all over the place and there isn't a lot of agreement about how to proceed.   That's why I'm really curious to hear what the God's stance is on this matter I can't tell if this is just some sort of glitch in the system or if someone is on the other end and really just not paying attention at all. But, this is the 4th chat in a row over the past 12 hours or so that I've entered a chat and just end up talking to myself for a while before giving up. In other news. I'm super excited for the NBA to start! I think they officially start next week.  But not possitive. I'm a big Washington Wizards fan There are just so many good teams to watch this year. I want to watch the opening games for the Wizards, Celtics, 76ers, Raptors, Jazz, Thunder, Rockets, Warriors and Lakers Seriously so much good talent to watch this year!  It's going to be super exciting! I have to go here in a bit. I went to the vet this morning with my dog to get her stitches out, but they forgot to take out a pair of stitches and so I have to go back again at 230.  So I need to leave in like 10 minutes Which means I have to get off of here in like 2. I'm just going to start getting ready now. Nice chatting with you chitchatter23! I'll probably end up talking to you for the fifth time in a row here in a couple of hours.  Because no one pays attention to their notifications and participates in this challenge. I'll just keep getting points for talking to myself all day I guess. Data is data. Bye now!

body: Hello! I have a sneaking suspicion that you're chitchatter23. If you are, I never get to talk to you anymore. Which is a shame. I really enjoyed our little talks. And if you're not, then, um, it's also good to talk to you! I haven't met anyone I haven't liked yet, so that's great. I'm always open to meeting new people; and I'm even more open to continuing to talk to those new people. It's so fun, all these people meeting and talking and being friendly and having no other purpose than to chat. Or, actually, I guess they DO have a purpose, but it's more prize-related and stuff. And the only way to get that prize is to chat, so, technically, it all comes down to chatting. But I don't like chatting on my own. It's kinda sad, and I don't want to mess up their metrics, you know? I don't think I'm trying to throw anything off; I just feel their data would be more accurate if there were two people talking. And that's not what I'm trying to do at all. I'd hope that any chat data is still viable, even if it's one-way, but that's a little cruel if it's not. I suppose they want two way communication, so listening to a single ramble isn't nearly as effective as a real two-person conversation. A conversation requires two parts; otherwise, it's just a monologue. Or maybe they're hunting for text patterns to emulate to make the person sound more human? See, I just don't know! In one case, it's okay to stay here and talk, and in the other, I should probably get off now. But I kinda enjoy the soliloquizing, if I do say so myself. Hey! I typed that word without red squigglies. That just made my day. And I'm even happier that I knew how to use that word in its proper context. I didn't even know I knew HOW to use that word--or that the word existed I guess my old days of Shakespeare are kicking in. So what do I do, though? I don't consider it wrong to stay here because I'm still giving them more data, but at the same time, I'm not certain about that. Oh, my goodness, is that the time? Eeef, never mind. I might have to get off soon, anyway. I have someone I need to tutor, and they live about half hour away. Plus, there's the whole "finish getting ready" part that I need to do, and that's going to take maybe ten minutes or something, I dunno. Not sure. But anyway, I can't stick around for much longer. It would've been nice to chat with you! It's okay, though. Maybe next time. If there is a next time. If not? Well, then at least we tried here. And it's okay. Not everything works out the first time you try. The important thing is to keep trying--or, in this case, to keep chatting! I'm sure I'll run into you for real when the time comes. Till then, I wish you the best of luck in whatever your endeavors are and hope everything else goes well! See you, okay?
