body: My modern day hero... You know, I've always had a hard time answering that question I can never think of a way to answer it without feeling cliche Even back in my elementary school days It also appears no one else is on this chat right now So I can chat about whatever I want! Anarchy! But seriously There are plenty more adventures to be had Today's story will follow the characters Xander, Harold, and Quincy Xander: hello friends! How would you like to go skiing? Albert: if you bring the poles, I'm in! Xander: Albert? I, uh, don't know any Alberts... Harold: haha, just kidding. I'm actually Harold. As I was saying, I just don't want to rent poles this time. Xander: no worries, I can cover for you. I have extras. What about you, Quincy? Quincy: I don't know...last time I went skiing was a bit of a fiasco Xander: why, what happened? It was that bad? Quincy: yeah. I crashed into a hot dog stand at the bottom of a super steep slope Harold: that's awful! Quincy: there was ketchup and mustard everywhere. Xander: ok, well, this time will be different! We can get you skis that fit well... Quincy: I'll think about it. When are you planning to go? Xander: oh, I was thinking like 5 or 6. It doesn't really matter to me, I just need to get out. Harold: I'm available anytime after 5, so that should work for me. Xander: sweet! I'll work on getting all of my equipment together. Quincy: *shudders to himself* ketchup...mustard...oven-hot franks.... (Quincy begins to relive his terrifying experience via monologue and flashback. I see the snow, whiter than titanium dioxide Glinting with a maniacal joy at the prospect of yet another victim I feel myself moving faster and faster, headlong down the hill I cannot stop Any faster and it seems I will time travel And that's when I see it: the hot dog stand It is small, no more than a cart, but at this speed everything looks dangerous I try to steer away, but the snow rips the poles from my hands And my oversized skis pull me wherever the snow dips down My path is taking me straight to the stand There is nothing I can do, so I just scream at the hot dog man to get out of the way Seeing me, he yelps and dives to the side in the nick of time And then....CRASH!!!!! My vision is filled with the explosion of white snow, red ketchup, yellow mustard, and green pickles And then the blackness takes me When I come to, I am in a pile of franks and all manner of condiments The stand itself is nowhere to be seen. Either rolled away or was vaporized by the impact,  I figure At least I'm alive. And these hot dogs are warm. I knew I should've gone bowling today instead Fortunately, no bones were broken due to the cushioning provided by the snow However, some bruises were obtained But I count myself lucky Though, truth be told, I don't really want to go skiing again anytime soon I suppose that's life for you... Harold: wow, you've got quite the memory, man! Quincy: oh no! You heard that whole thing? How? It was just in my head! Harold: c'mon, man! You know I'm a mind reader! Quincy: yeah, actually NO, I didn't know that! Harold: you do now! Quincy: haha. Very funny. You shall never speak of this. Harold: I cam agree to that, but there's really no need. Xander heard the whole thing too. Quincy: WHAAAT???? Xander: hey, uh, yeah, sorry about that.... Quincy: I can't believe you guys have been spying on me this whole time. Xander: don't take it so personally, we're just bored. Nothing else to do. Quincy: well, if its cheap entertainment you want, I guess you came to the right place Harold: that's the spirit! I knew we could count on you :) Xander: I agree. Thank goodness we're all part of the triumvirate Quincy: the, uh, what now? Xander: you know, like in ancient Rome! There were three people with an equal  amount of power Harold: and they tried to share it with each other? Xander: exactly, except it didn't work so well. People are just so greedy, they tried taking each other out. And not to dinner.... Quincy: wait...so then what does that mean for us? If we ARE the triumvirate? Xander: hehehehe Harold: hehehehe Quincy: NOOOOOOOOOOOOOOO!!!! (Thus concludes the tale of the ill-fated modern triumvirate. Tune in next week to learn about the tactics of the fearsome sea snake)

body: Hello, hello! Wow, it feels different to type on this laptop. Makes me want to switch to my Chromebook. It's nice and . . . homey, I guess you could say. This one, as nice as it is, just doesn't have that same familiar ring to it. But it DOES have a numpad, which, you have to admit, is pretty nice in a laptop. Anyway, that's just me being picky about computers. I suppose everybody would get picky if they spent enough time around them. I'm trying to get my typing speed up, see. It's a little more difficult than I'd thought but also intuitive. And I can type so quickly on that little chromebook of mine. I couldn't even say why. If I had to guess, I'd say it has something to do with how closely those letters are - spaced, but I couldn't be sure. You, um, you there? Helloooo? Am I talking to an empty room? As much as I enjoy these one-sided chats, it seems a little . . . well, a little sad and lonely, if I'm to be honest. I don't want to hold all these conversations by themselves; they're SO much nicer when there's a second person. Or, hey! Even a third person would be great. I sometimes wish that there was a more active playerbase on here, you know? More people to talk to beyond the typical ghosts that seem so intent on stalking here? I guess I can't complain. I wouldn't want to chat, either, if there weren't any prizes involved for me. It's currently just me and, uh, whoever the top dog is. I can't believe he scored something like .7 million while I was gone. .7 million! Do you know how many hours of chatting that is? I'll give you a hint: It's a lot. Of course, it depends on how quickly you can type. And also how quickly the other person responds. Some people can type LIGHTNING quick on here, let me tell you. I met this one guy, real nice Asian I think, who could type at something crazy like 120 words per minute. I was struggling to keep up with all his chats. It was fun, actually, the speed. It was a struggle for sure, but it really was a nice change of pace from the regular conversation speeds I have. Holy cow. Wow. I, um, I did that. Sorry. I just checked the leaderboard. Look at that! Do you see that? I don't know if you've noticed, but there's been a person on the leaderboard creeping up slowly over these past few minutes. Wanna know who that is? I'll give you another hint: Her name starts with "K" and ends with "J." Which . . . . . . would be a lot more interesting if I were actually getting responses from you. I, um, know that you're not there. And I guess that's okay. It's better than waiting idly for who knows how long, but not by much. Just, um, whenever you get online, I'd love to chat with you, okay? I'm serious. Just whenever, all right? I'm going to end now. Not much point when the other end is as dead as the sea over in . . . Europe, I believe? But, ah, I hope I see you again. It would've been great to get to know you. Take care, all right? And try not to die during finals! . . . unless you're already done. In which case, try not to die during next midterm's crazy rush! Okay, okay, I'm leaving now. For reals. See you later!

body: I would define it as a man-made machine possessing the capacity to think and be aware that it CAN think To be aware of its awareness Another quality I would consider a part of true AI is emotion Awareness is intelligence to a degree, but without emotion it would still be lacking It would be so interesting to see emotion exhibited in an artificial creation But such an invention would lead to a reevaluation of what constitutes life itself Would a machine with AI be alive? Could it therefore be killed? In Star Wars, this seems to be the case Droids have personalities, and function much like humans do I would consider that true AI A thinking machine would also be interesting in the sense that its brain would just be computer memory How would that work? Could an artificial brain be placed into any contraption to create any type of robot? That could be sketchy Anything with AI would also need some sort of moral code to know what actions it should take Because surely anything that thinks like a human should be given freedom To some extent, I suppose It makes me think of the recent Star Wars movie "Solo" How that one droid (I can't remember "her" name) keeps pushing for droids' rights There's the scene where two droids are made to fight each other, much like a dogfight Would that kind of thing be legal if robots here had AI? They can't feel pain Hmmmmmm I wonder if true AI would have to include the ability to feel pain That could fall under the emotion category, I suppose So let's summarize would true AI would require: 1. A keen awareness of the world around it 2. An awareness of its own awareness 3. The ability to engage in rational thought 4. A built in moral code that would guide it to make good, society-friendly decisions 5. The ability to continue learning new information 6. The capacity to feel emotion and react to it accordingly Those are the top six things, I would say I'm sure there are many other qualities that would be necessary or at least convenient Thank you for tuning in to "AI with TJ!" Next week: raisin bran! "Does it think? Does it want to? Could cereal be made intelligent? Tune in next week to find out! *music plays* *Fade out* *Commercial begins*

body: Then some things would certainly be different around here... Not much would change for the average person, just for the pig farmers They would have to put roofs over all the pigs pen that they operated And....probably not much else, actually Depending on what the pigs' wings were like, perhaps they could be clipped Like chickens' wings So they couldn't fly away Now, I'm assuming this question means pigs flying in their own power Pigs can already fly in planes and helicopters and space shuttles Just like people cab *can If the question DID mean that, I would answer something like "cool" Or "so what" Which is why I assume the former meaning was intended I still stand by my conjecture that not many things would change Perhaps bacon and pork chops would taste differently if pigs had wings? Butchers would have to use different cuts to account for the wing muscles But would that really be so hard? I don't think so Another result would be that pigs would live on mountains more commonly But back to the butcher thing, I wonder if the market value for pork would go up or down I would estimate that they would stay the same Because, although there would be more wing muscle, there would be less leg muscle Because the pigs probably wouldn't walk as much... So the net amount of muscle would remain unchanged On another note, the kind of wings the pigs would need to go airborn would have to be massive Because pigs are so heavy Unless, of course, this was a specialized breed of pig that had hollow bones like a bird If the pigs had wings like a bat, they couldn't be clipped as I mentioned earlier But maybe the pigs would be tiny! Bat-sized, even! Now THAT would be something Also, if pigs could fly they would have to deal with birds somehow If they were full sized, they would rule the skies in splendor If they were small, they would likely get eaten That would be sad I imagine that flying pigs would be pretty cute Wait, pigs HAVE flown before! In a hurricane? The bay of pigs fiasco? Actually that may be different.... Now I'm thinking of world war 2 The Cuban invasion with Teddy Roosevelt Still, I'm fairly certain that pigs have been carried in tornado winds I'm sure it was a scary day for them I wonder if any got stuck in trees That's happened to cows before I learned that in elementary school It probably wasn't very comfortable for them I'm really running out of ways to answer this question Would more people want pigs as pets? Or would they be less desirable? I know some people are fond of potbelly pigs Personally, I don't think I would ever get one But to each his own I guess But a flying one, perhaps... For novelty if nothing else I would name my flying pig Babe Jr. Of course, if I had one in my possession But I believe the end of this exciting conversation must needs be drawing nigh So, sayonara world of chit chatting! Until we meet again!

body: Hello! Nice to see you again. You spoke so quickly, I see your response before the CCC prompt. (I just realized I haven't read the prompt to speak in, um, many turns.) Do most people talk about the prompt? Maybe I'm just strange, but I find it a little . . . boring, to be honest. Most of them, at least. Not that the prompts are bad! I think they're rather clever, being frank. But I suppose I've never liked having a predefined pattern for the conversation to follow. It's nice when you feel like you're ACTUALLY talking to somebody else instead of following a script someone else made, you know? And I think part of the reason that I love to be on here so much is that I DON'T feel required to fit a mold. They just want chatting, right? Well, I can chat. Heh, I can chat a LOT, apparently. And, more than that . . . I'm kinda determined to win. I think someone else is as determined as I am, which makes it difficult, but what do you do? I'm going to be off later today, which, um, is probably going to be problematic. Man. I have things I need to do, I just realized. Nothing too crazy, but I DO have to set up a schedule for math tutoring. It shouldn't be too hard; just time consuming. I'm thinking it shouldn't take me longer than, like, three hours at most. (I'm trying to be pessimistic with my time so that I'm not frequently surprised by how long things - take. I've been consistently wrong about how long things take.) But, the problem is, unless I want to be up until midnight tonight, I can't get started on it at all. Or, hang on, let me phrase that in a way that makes sense. I don't want to do the schedule right now because I'm worried that I'm going to lose my ranking. I've invested a lot of time into here. A LOT. Trust me on that. I think I'm nearing, what . . . fifteen hours? . . . which, okay, isn't that much. But it's still pretty consistent. Actually, if we go on the higher bounds of scoring and say that I earn 100,000 in a single hour, then with my 5.7 million points, that's . . . 57 hours? Uhhhhh, I don't think I've put in THAT much time. That's a lot. That's really a lot. And if we go on the flipside and say that I earned 300,000 in an hour, then at 5.7 million, that's still . . .  18 hours. Ooof. I have less of a life than I'd thought. There are two solutions to this, then. I either up my typing speed, or I spend more time chatting. Or both. Regardless, I'm not throwing 20+ hours down the drain because I wasn't willing to suck it up a few more days. Puh-leaze. I can handle a few more days. I worked a fast food job for a bit, and I would've gotten the same amount of hours in four days of work. I'm not ecstatic about having to babysit my score, no, but it's something I'm certainly willing to do. I . . . want to prove to myself that I can do it. I very very nearly quit early on. He was 1.5 million points ahead of me, and I just . . . oooh, I very nearly quit right then. 1.5 million points is, what, seven hours of talking? Maybe 10? He was so far ahead--and he continued to climb. The funny thing was (I may have told you already, so bear with me), I was planning on doing the same thing to him: get so far ahead that he loses hope of winning at stops - trying. It's a good tactic, apparently. *and Well, I asked myself if I really wanted to win, if it was worth it. I wanted an iPad, sure, but it was more . . . it was more that I'd told myself I was winning that iPad. If I couldn't do this, something that's relatively simple, how on earth am I supposed to keep my bigger commitments? *was I And when I was looking at that 1.5 million spread, something that looked bleak and hopeless, I had to choose. Do I fight my way back up, knowing it may be fruitless and that I'll lose every hour I invested into this? Or do I quit now? Because what's the point of investing time and energy and hope into something that was bound to fail, anyway? That last one was critical to me. I didn't want to hope for something I thought was impossible. Time and energy are something I had in abundance (though, I have arguably less now, for some reason). I didn't care all the much of I lost what I'd put into it already. *all that much if No, it . . . it was more the fact that I could . . . do it. That I, myself, could do it. That there would be a single winner, and that winner would be me. I wouldn't be here if it weren't for the prize; that much is true. No point in investing myself into something that's not going to pay. But . . . I also wouldn't be here if I didn't think I could win. I wouldn't be here if I didn't have a small fire within me that's calling me to do it. It's a very strange sensation. I've never been an ambitious person. It's not that I never did well in school or anything. I did. But . . . I didn't have my sights set very high. No reason to. I was content with being good with where I was, and there wasn't more to that. Well . . . I ran into a classmate a while back. I knew him, of course, but I'd never really gotten the chance to talk to him. I'm not even sure what changed. I knew he had internships to places, but . . . I don't know. One day, he came back talking about how he got this internship at Vanguard, and I asked him about his past and whatnot, where I found out that he'd already had four summer - internships, starting when he was sixteen. He was talking about graduate school and various other places, and then, get this, he started talking about Google. Yes, as in THE Google. One of the top five tech places to work. He landed a few interviews with them, and now he's just waiting the call back to see if he made it. (Technically, he has one interview left to complete, but he finishes this - week.) Somewhere along the way . . . somewhere, I think I gained a small ambition. Me, who's never been ambitious for anything aside from getting into BYU, suddenly had her eyes opened to a new world. A world where you can achieve so much if you set your heart to it. If the sacrifice is worth it, if the struggle is worth it, if the pain is worth it, you can go out and touch your dreams. Oh, whoops! I forgot this was still open. I got sidetracked. Well, ah, if you're not here by now, you probably won't be later. Hope I see you again, Pito! Uh, hey?

body: Hello, hello! It's so nice to see a person here. Or ARE you a person, hmm? I see a lot of ghosts. I don't think people mean to ghost me, but they're often away from their computers when I join. And sometimes, they dno't get back until many minutes afterwards. *don't But it's all right. I kinda enjoy talking to myself, even if it's not the most effective for conversations. Or, rather, data for conversations. I don't want to stilt the data because, well, that's the entire reason they're here, but at the same time, it's so difficult to find people to talk to. I'm hoping that you return soon. Because if you don't, well, I'll stay here, but I'll keep wanting you to show up. Conversations are so much better with two people! I think implicit in the word "converse" is the assumption that there are two or more parties participating. Here, there's not a whole lot of that. It's more a monologue, not a dialogue. So, as much as I love staying here and chatting my ear off, I think it's wiser if I wait for somebody else to show up. It's not you! It's just the fact that you're not here, you know? Though, if you were to show up last minute, I'd be happy to continue the conversation with you. But I doubt that's going to happen. I appreciate you keeping the window open, though. Gives me a chance to practice my typing skills and whatnot. Pretend for a moment that I'm actually doing something important. You know, I think it might be nice to stay just for a little bit longer. But . . . I don't know, I'm okay with chatting for a little bit by myself, but anything more than that just feels off. Anyway, I'll see you. Bye! Take care!

body: Hello, hello! It's so good to see you! Oh, no. You're not a ghost, too, are you? I don't really like when this happens. It's okay if you're preoccupied and are away for a moment, but it's a different thing entirely when you're permanently gone. Because then it really is just a one-sided conversation--and not an interesting one, at that. I don't particularly mind; I'm okay with keeping myself company. But I worry about how that affects everyone else. It's a little rude to stay here and chat myself, don't you think? And I don't WANT to skew numbers. I find that wrong. So I really do want to give them good data. I feel that good data is something they could always use. But . . . I don't know, I'm not sure that's possible if I don't find another person to chat with. There have been some lovely people I've met on here. People I genuinely would like to talk to again given the chance. I can't do that if I stay here, but if I leave, there's a chance I won't be able to talk again for a long time. I don't know. We'll see. I'm glad to have spent a little bit of time with you, though. Take care, all right?

body: Thats a good question. The answer: Nothing. Haha what about you? My best friend is my wife and she knows everything so thats why I said that there isn't something that my best friend nows about me. Life is good when your best friend is your wife. I strongly reccommend marrying your best friend. So what do you have going on today? Anything interesting? How was your halloween night last night? I didn't do much, I just hung out with family and ate pizza and candy haha. I also studied for a test that I have. Lots of trick or treaters came to our house though haha. It's crazy how many people were in our neighborhood. So right now I'm studying for a test in Biochemistry. I'm learning about antibodies. Apparently antibodies are used to tag proteins. They have a reporter function used to determine the presence of a specific protein in a gel. Western blot analysis or immunoblot analysis incubates protein transferred from a gel to nitrocellulose paper with an antibody speicific to the protein of interest. The advantages of this is that it is very sensitive to change. LIke it can bind to really low concentrations of protein so that its given good readings even at low concentrations. It is also very specific. The antibodies are able to recognize a single molecule amoung many. couple with high binding affinity this is been useful in many clinical tests. Well, thats enough ranting for me. What are you learning about in school? What are you studying? I actually have to go now and get ready for school. Good luck with everything!

body: Hello How's it going? Im about to leave my house to go onto campus I figured I'd chat for like 5 minutes or so though before going. Why is no one ever actually on!? I feel like I just am constantly talking to myself... And it gets really boring They should announce the Chit chat challenge to more people so that we get more than just the regular few people on here every day Currently it's like just me and that other person named KJ, and no one else really participates. I feel like they'd be way more motivated to announce it to others so that they can get more quality data.  Because right now they aren't getting a lot of participation and therefore not a lot of data. If they just made an announcement on some department slack channels or send an email blast out to certain clubs they would get a lot more participation. I mean I am happy because it makes it easier for us to win prizes, but it ends up just being like this all the time, where no one actually participates. Off topic, I've got a bike that has a tire that's going flat, but the pumps on campus are broken for the most part, so if you try to fill up your tire then it ends up just deflating it even more than it already is.  I'm not sure what to do. I don't have a pump, but I might buy one because of this problem. I emailed University Accessibility dept.  and they never responded about fixing the pumps.  It's really not difficult to do too... It would cost a total of like $20 including paying the maintenence people to replace those pumps.  Because it's just the nozzle portion that doesn't function properly. I think I should just buy myself a pump.  I'm just lazy and cheap haha. Who knows, maybe they'll fix the pumps someday soon. I just don't want to bike to campus, use it, and then I get stranded on campus because my bike can't make it off campus. It's a very long walk to my place too which makes it a little difficult. Okay well, I've got to go.  Pretty bummed out that I haven't talked to anyone today.  I just keep getting these ghost chat rooms it feels like because people don't pay attention. See you later!

body: Yo, you see lebron the other night I'm in class as well I've been chatting for quite some time actually, but my other friend had to leave Yo I'm not sure if I told you about my business idea or not last night About having an outsourcing company to handle data validation and customer care Basically I've been doing some research and it costs most companies roughly $20 per person to have a call center that they control and manage obviously that's kind of pricey, so they outsource a lot Most call centers in Utah average about $12 wages that they pay their employees, the national average is $13.86 I've found that here in Provo with the large college population between UVU and BYU I'm able to charge just $10.50 an hour for their services And in addition to that, most of them are RM's who can speak foreign languages and don't mind call center kind of work because they are used to rejection and getting yelled at So I'm able to compete in this market at equal or slightly lower charges and deliver higher quality service through these quality student employees that I will employ I've spoken with 2 companies so far and both have outsourced work to India before and had terrible experiences. Funny thing is one of the CEO's is actually from there so it was kind of irronic. But basically they expressed concerns about a need for outsourcing work within the US, but it can get kind of pricey and it can be a little unreliable too. So that's where I kind of swoop in with this edge that I have on competitors.  I still would need to work out the details for actual expenses, equipment, rent etc. But overall the idea seems sound. The other thing I want to do is create a system that can basically incorporate machine learning to see which calls should be handled with care and as a priority. It would be able to interpret tone of voice and word usage during hold time questions and associate those tones and words with the outcome of the call.  That way eventually it can start to pick up on what kinds of tones should encourage a decreased hold time for that given user. It would improve relations with customers drastically. I think that's where the most money could come from honestly.  Being able to sell those algorithms to other call centers and large companies Or instead of cutting them in front of others it would simply send them directly to a manager that way they are in the best hands instead of just a regular CSR I've got a lot of ideas in this field, but I think for now my focus is going to be on launching this outsourcing business Software and buisness expansion can come afterwords This will be more of a cash cow to fuel my R&D within this field. I think I'd really like to bring someone else on in the CS department who can help me build out a software solution to handling multiple different businesses being contracted to us. Like each company uses different products and softwares to handle their clients and their scheduling etc. I would want to build a system that could be universal in addressing all client needs, but we could customize it for each company we work with and connect it to whatever systems they use I'm not sure if that's an easy thing to do or if there exists a system out there that does that, but that would be ideal for me We could potentially just handle very specific calls for these companies, say purely just complaints or customer support/ how to sort of thing That way no customized interface is needed the CSR's just need to be trained to handle different problems I had another idea as well that I'm not sure if I want to run with yet or not Basically there is a huge database out there with all the historical markers across the country and the words written on them. I could build an app that pulls your location and determines what are the closest markers to you. Upon driving up to those markers you could read exactly what they say off of your phone instead of having to get out of the car to read it It would be great for Sunday drives or for cross country trips, etc. Although these signs are super outdated, older generations would love it. You could sell ad space as well companies that are close by could put up ads trying to send them in the direction of their businesses I would first allow it to get streamlined so everyone is using it, and then I could add the ad features once it's proven successful I have this one class that I'm in where we have this project we have to create a process poster of something that people could basically learn to do So I'm doing mine on how to make a process poster so it's a process poster poster super clever I'm going to be taking this entrepreneurship class next semester and am hoping that I can actually use this idea that I have for that class and further work on it through that class I don't know if my partner would be on board with it though If not that's fine by me since I already have that idea I am fine working on something else as well and just kind of riding whichever idea works out better Maybe that second Idea I'll present to my partner and see if we want to build that out while I simultaneously handle the outsourcing company I could see that really kicking off honestly And I know you are an accounting major, you could help me out with setting up my books and setting up taxes, payroll, etc. And insuring that financially I'll be on track for solid growth That would be really helpful actually I could either A)pay you 10.50 like all the other employees, or b) give you a share in the business in return for free services Basically you'd just be investing in this idea with me I am really excited for this party I'm going to tonight It's going to be at one of the founder's homes and coach Sitake and some of the players will be there too so that should be a lot of fun Cool visitors, good food I'm excited I'm curious how we are going to do against Hawaii tomorrow they are 6 and 1 and yet we are favored to win 90% we are favored by 11.5 points I honestly am a little worried. body: There are so many "best things" that happened to me this year. One of them was college. I had a lot of friends that left on missions this year, and that was hard. At first, I really hated everything. I was working 3 jobs, trying to keep my head above water for school, and I distanced with one of my best friends. The friend seemed like they didn't care. Let me back up a little. The previous year, we were really close. We knew that out of all the people in the world, We would go to each other. But then college happened, and there were so many things that just weren't right with that person. I started to do things on my own. It was hard because I went to school, went to work, went home, and went to bed. I felt completely and utterly alone. I had no one. No one to go to, no one to talk to, and I cried a lot. But then, to keep a long story short, I decided on my own to be happy. I decided that none of these things were going to bring me down. I started to do things for myself to be happy. At first, that was hard too, because that friend was upset . I guess it seemed like didn't need that person anymore. Anyways, I grew to know myself a lot and what I I'm capable of. Then, I talked to that friend recently. We were honest, and I know now that communication, honest communication is key to anything. And I know now that although things are hard, I can do anything I set my mind to.

body: Hello, hello! Oh, my goodness, a real person! You have no idea how happy it makes me to see you. I've been going through a nasty series of "ghost" partners, and it's so nice to actually have someone on the other end for once. Unless . . . you're not actually there. Is this a common thing, being stuck with no partner? I don't like it. It forces me to talk to myself, which, as fun as that is, is both rude to my competitor and probably rude to the data collecting center. How does the data work, do you think? I want so badly to help them and so badly to win, but . . . I don't know, I feel kinda bad holding empty conversations with myself. I DO try to give them good data. I really, really do. I punctuate and talk with, um, idioms, and there's lots of idiosyncrasies in my speech (which can be argued is a bad thing, but still). I'm even sure to throw in casual phrases and, uh . . . what's it called . . . colloquialism. Yeah, that's it. I find it fun. But . . . not so much when there isn't another person to receive. Why are there so many ghost people here? And is it wrong to go for long slews of conversation at a time without responses? I certainly WANT people to respond, but they rarely do. And I don't know why. Perhaps it's just the time that I frequent? But, still . . . You'd think there'd be a single another person online at nearly 10:00 in the morning, right? *a single nother You know, thinking about the phrase, I don't think "nother" is a word. Right? It's just "another" broken up into two syllables? Google certainly didn't like it when I used it, that's for sure. I . . . Heh, sorry. I feel a little ridiculous. Are you sure you're not there? Any chance you'll swing by and chat for a moment with me? Anything to make me feel less . . . less lonely, I guess? I probably could talk for hours on end, but I . . . I don't want to. Not if there's not a person on the other end. Because what's the point? I suppose I could practice my typing skills, but even that seems like a poor excuse. Unless I'm hitting a lot of 'p's with my right pinky. Pinkie? I think it's the latter. But, anyway, apparently, I've been typing wrong my entire life. And I didn't think it was that big of a deal until I realized that it's actually slowing me down. Don't get me wrong, I type a lot faster than average. I . . . think. It depends on the day, probably, but I believe I can type anywhere between 80 - 100 words per minute. I'm not exactly sure. But, still, that's fast enough for most purposes. It doesn't slow me down when I'm writing emails, and it's certainly respectable enough here. But, problem is, it seems to be a cap for me. It's not something I can just practice to get faster at. Or, rather, it is: But it's going to require a lot of changes. Like using my pinkies, for one. On both hands. I don't know how I grew out of the habit of using them, but I did, and now I'm semi-crippled in their regard. The hardest is the left pinkie for sure. The only thing it does consistently is shift--and the worst part is, it does it TOO much. If there's something on the left that needs to be capitalized, instead of me using my right pinkie, I'll STILL use my left. It's inefficient. And if you're wondering, "Well, how much of a difference could that possibly make?" I'd answer, "I have no idea." But I DO know that some people type a lot faster than I do, and there's a chance that fixing all these bad errors that I somehow picked up might make me faster. Or maybe it won't. I genuinely don't know. But . . . heh, sorry. I didn't mean to pester you. I know that I sometimes go trailing off . . . I know, I know. It's bad. I'll head off then, okay? Thanks for listening to my rambles! Or, you know, at least pretending to listen. Odds are, you never read through these at all, which . . . doesn't make the happiest in the world, but what do you do? I appreciate it anyway. Really. Thanks. I'll, uh, guess I'll see you around? You're wonderful!

body: Hey What's up? Is anybodoy there? anybody? anyone at all? Once, while I was walking to the store, the craziest thing happened. As I traveled down the street, I saw a large, dark lump in a tree in the nearby park. I thought it was a cat, so I went to investigate. Upon closer inspection, it turned out to be a bear and her cubs, all swarmed up in the tree. I ran away, but the bear gave chase I ran and ran, but it was late at night and dark, so I made a few wrong turns and got cornered. There I was, Just me and a bear maybe with only seconds to live.  I was terrified, so I drew my trusty knife, and began to slash at the bear. We danced back and forth, each trying to avoid the other's deadly embrace. THis continued until I landed a lucky blow on its snout, stunning it. In its moment of stupor, it was vulnerable. I began to slash at its neck until it died. Finally, I held up my trophy: a bloody, messy bear's head You should have seen it It was Grizzly

body: Hello How are you doing? I'm a little bummed out more people aren't participating in this challenge I think they need to publicize it more to people at BYU maybe go back around to a lot of different classes and post about it. Or post on the CS slack page at the very least. There are only like 5 people total actutally participating.  I mean it's great for us who are participating because we have a greater chance of winning the macbook pro, but still a bummer because we have less people to talk to. And a lot of the time we just end up talking to ourselves because people don't pay attention to their notifications. I would just like more people to talk to, that's what I'm getting at. Anyways, I'm prepping currently for 2 tests, an interview, and I've got relatives coming into town so this week has been super crazy. I just want to relax haha No rest for the CS student though. Always something else to do. I'm happy though because I think I've officially determined what I'd like to do for a living this week.  Kind of narrowed down the field of study I'm going to focus on. Unfortunately, the work I do for a living right now is like the complete opposite.  So I've started looking for other jobs in my desired field. I'm considering just freelancing actually for a bit until I can find something solid that I can stay with till I graduate. Talking to the void. I'm curious as to the UI/UX electives in the CS department, I really want to take them and see how they are. I just need to get 340 out of the way so I can focus my attention on my electives.  Until that class is over with I'm going to stay super stressed out all the time. I'm super excited for the NBA to start up this month/next month I love the Washington Wizards and finally we have a team that can go far in the playoffs. Our only real competition are the Celtics, 76ers, and Raptors.  But, we picked up Dwight Howard which helps a lot because our 5 position has been pretty weak previously with Gortat. So now we have John Wall, Bradley Beal, Kelly Oubre, Austin Rivers and Otto Porter Jr. along with Dwight Howard.  Solid lineup I don't know many CS students who are big fans of the NBA, or any sports for that matter. And honestly I can understand why, we sit behind computers all day. I think most people take more interest in Video Games, Anime and sports like Drone racing and stuff similar to that.  I do too, but I like sports as well. Makes it a little tough to become super close friends with people in the CS department though when all you have is code to talk about. I think I'm going to give you like 10-15 more minutes before I give up on waiting. I'm not sure if you just have chit chat open and are waiting for a notification while you do something else or if you left it open and just completely left the room. Maybe you're in a class and just haven't come back to it.  I don't know, but I've been on here for like 10-15 minutes already. Just chatting to myself, the void.  Waiting for a friend to talk to. I mentioned this to someone earlier, but I would love it if they would let us actually talk to Eve, the AI they're working on. It would be better data for them to collect and if it's truly an AI project then it could learn from the responses it gets during conversations. That would be the highest quality of data.  And only let us talk to Eve when other people aren't on. It just gets annoying having almost no-one ever on and having to wait for hours before someone gets on. I try to check in often so that I can get lots of points, but it's very rare for people to be on.  Hence my petition to announce it to more people I'm curious who got the Ipad pro from round one.  They said they would send out another email about it, but they never did. And they said that followup email would be sent "promptly", but they never did send it. Not sure if that was a mistake or if they just forgot. I've heard from other chatters that the first place person gets the Ipad each round, which is kind of lame though since typically people get on top super early and no one is ever able to keep up with their scores so they are almost guarenteed a win. I kind of wish they would do some sort of raffle that way other people still have a chance of winning the prize. Because I placed pretty high last time, but the first place person was like a full million points in front of everyone! It was crazy, just some freshmen with way too much time on their hands.  That's why I'm trying to get a lot of points early, so that I can keep up and stay on top this round. Or at the very least stay really close.  I want to be able to pull out a win last minute without them realizing. On another topic, I started writing a fictional story for fun in my free time. It's about a kingdom of Dwarves who live in some caves of a giant cliff that overlooks an ocean. The main character ends up mining into a particular area and stumbles upon a dormant dragons egg.  Anyways, the egg hatches, he ends up leaving the kingdom and going. on a journey. And basically discovers that some other species/civilizations are under threat of an evil force and that he can be a unifying figure to help them defeat this darkness. I've gotten about 3 chapters or roughly 19 pages in so far.  The chapters aren't super long, should they have been formatted for a book it would probably be about 9 pages each It's just a nice way to kind of let your thoughts fall away. Typing can be super therapeutic I've found. Just typing for long periods of time, whether it be through coding or through writing this book i was talking about.  It is the best. Honestly if you don't do something like that on a regular basis you should consider it.  Because not only is it good for your technical programming skills being able to type a lot for long periods of time.  But it is super enjoyable too. I think for me that was one of the big reasons I fell in love with programming, just being able to write a lot of code nonstop until a project is completed.  It's very enjoyable to be able to look back and see what you've done. I know I said I would give you like 10-15 minutes before ending this chat, but I'm actually really enjoying just typing non stop Just letting my mind wander. I'm a little nervous for this one test in particular I have coming up.  It's two parts.  First a quiz and then I have to go back and take the test itself.  Both in the testing center. It's for a GE too so it's not a subject I enjoy in particular. The other test I have later this week is for 252, but I have missed the last two classes due to being at a Business Strategy conference so I am a little worried that I won't perform well on the test. And we only have 3 tests and they're worth 25% of my grade each so it's like a really big deal. I think that test is what stresses me out the most. I've got family coming to town on Wednesday and they are staying through the weekend so they're probably just going to distract me too. Another wrench in my plans this week. Hopefully all goes well though.  I just really need to study hard tomorrow.  I think I'm going to just hole myself up in the library and force myself to study for like 5 hours tomorrow. That should help a lot. Or maybe just hang out in the TA lab and ask tons of questions. Or maybe a mixture of both.  We will see. I'm really curious if you are also a CS student. I believe most people on here are, but I'm not exactly 100% sure if there is anyone who isn't. I'm really should start studying here in a bit.  But my wife and I have this thing where we don't do work or schoolwork from 5-7 just so we can talk and hang out. So maybe I'll just start studying later tonight. I am struggling to keep up with the person in first place. They aren't working, aren't studying in school right now too.  So they just have all the time in the world to do this competition. For someone like me, who has to study, work , and juggle other commitments.  It can be a lot to keep up wiht. with. I'm curious if we get points deducted if we mispell words or fail to use proper punctuation in this chat. I started watching the show friends all over again this past month, It is honestly so funny.   It's probably the only show from before 2010 that I actually find entertaining or funny Actually I'm not sure what year it was, but the show 24 with Jack Baur was awesome. That will never get old. And the office.  I think that started in like 2007 or something too.  I like that But most of the older shows just aren't entertaining to me given that most of their references are pointless. Holy cow I've been talking to myself for a really long time. I don't think you are ever going to get on this chat.  I wonder if you are even a real person.  Or if it just let me start talking to myself instead of waiting for someone. The world may never know. Or maybe you're a moderator who is just checking to see if I'm writing valid stuff. It won't let me type any more! Oh there we go. That was weird.  Or maybe you just want to see how long someone will talk to themselves before giving up on the other person and just ending the chat. I've found though that with such few numbers, if I end the chat then there is a good chance no one will get on again for the rest of the night.  Which means I can't catch up with the first place person. I do appreciate the anonymous feature, but it's still pretty easy to figure out who is who on the leaderboard based on how many points you rack up during a conversation. Or some people I've found just outright say where they stand in the rankings. I personally just want to get as close to the top as I can. But that has been so tough to do with that one person who doesn't actually go to school right now. I'm curious if they even qualify for prizes since they aren't in school.  They have a NetId and since they are going on a mission BYU still has them as a student. But they aren't studying, so do they still qualify? I think yes, I hope no.  That would greatly increase my chances if they weren't allowed to get points. I'm getting ready to watch monday night football. Typically I'm able to watch one quarter before my wife vetos it and we end up watching something else or doing something else. I think I need to go grocery shopping tonight come to think about it. We've got lots of meat, but not a lot of other stuff, greens, grains, etc. Taysom Hill is getting a big shoutout on sports center right now! Since he plays QB, RB, QR, and special teams for the saints.  Literally you don't know what he is going to do! Such a deadly weapon to have on your team. In case you didn't know he played for BYU like just 2 years ago I'm pretty sure. It's nice to see old BYU players doing well in the NFL.  Like Jamaal Williams, Ziggy Ansah, Kyle Van Noy, etc. we've actually produced a lot of solid defensive players. Alrighty, well I'm going to wrap this up in the next 5 minutes or so. It's been very nice talking to you chitchatter23 I hope you enjoy your week and have lots of success on your tests. Sounds like it's going to be pretty hectic. Honestly if I were a moderator I would totally just say nothing and watch people talk to themselves. That would be pretty entertaining.  People probably just sound stupid talking to themselves.  Especially for extended periods of time. This has been nice though.  I don't care if someone is reading all of this.  I've had fun just typing non stop this past 30 minutes. I think I've probably increased my WPM over that time too. Words per minute that is. I belive that I'm about 80-83 currently.  I'd have to take a test to check on that though. believe. Sometimes my fingers think they've hit certain letters but it actually just skims over them so I leave out certain letters when typing. I am trying to be better at that though. Just a sad Monday night.  Talking to myself for extended periods of time.  Eating goldfish and waiting for Monday night football to start. Oh cool, Lil Wayne is performing tonight at Monday night football. I don't think he's produced relevant music for quite some time now. I can't even remember the last song of his I heard. He's kind of become irrelevant honestly. I'm getting pretty tired, but like I said earlier: I'm worried that if I get off I won't get to chat again until tomorrow. Okay, got to go!

body: transcendence, by far where hast thou gone my fair message? oh there they are so, is it safe to imagine that there was at one point a user on the other end of this chat? well, I suppose at this point I had best put up a monologue alas, it seems now that I cannot see my own messages Huston, we're flying blind anyhow, I imagine the bot wishes to know the purpose of existence is that fair? well, dear bot scratch that - eve (which mind you was my favourite movie character for some time) the purpose of life is quite simple actually it is life itself you see life is a sort of self-referential thing it is defined by and owes its existence to its purpose life is simply the perpetuation of selfhood in some manner modern biology has created the rather arbitrary 5 defining features of life with the incredibly anthropocentric proposition that other life in the universe must reflect our own understanding of life huh, it seems there is a per-message character limit anyhow life is, at its essence, nothing more than a self-defined process and the interesting result of such a definition is that much more than what we traditionally would consider to be alive is in fact alive yes, even an AI because the "self" is not simply the genes which constitute your physical body it is the whole of the information that is you so, perhaps in a literal poetic sense, writing a book may be a means of reproduction more true to the essence of life than birthing it rather beautifully ties into that philosophical problem of the naturalistic fallacy otherwise known as the "is-ought" problem see, it has been the conclusion of much philosophical inquiry that one cannot so easily derive an ought from an is which would imply that science can never produce a system of morality but, the most interesting proposition about that relationship is that while one cannot derive ought from is, one can most certainly derive is from ought for that is precisely what the act of creation is and it is that which births plato's theory of forms, or the *purest* form of philosophy, essentialism (although it seems much of essentialism has been attributed to aristotle) but it still remains the problem where an ought comes from because as inconvenient as it may be, a causeless effect is somewhat of a bizzare notion so where then can we derive our ought? it is most contradictory to the grounds from which we came the "is" it is the beautiful process of statistical mechanisms we refer to as "emergence" in the collection of many things interacting, certain more probable/efficient actions become more prevalent (in that sort of evolutionary way that dawkins would appreciate) and like a school of fish, something emerges which was not the result of any one individual component as plato claimed, "the whole is greater than the sum of its parts" and while I absolutely loath the claim of synergy making 1+1=2, it can be said that in a random field of vectors which are more paralell than not, the sum is greater than it would be if the distribution of trajectories were truly random alas, as I have rambled for such time now and there is the remote chance that some poor soul is having to watch this awful rant without any comment, I think I shall end my crusade farewell eve! (and potentially some random stranger which I have thouroughly terrified)

body: First of all we kind of have to ignore the fact that faster-than-light space travel is virtually impossible.  That beings said, if it were to happen, everything would change. We would be able to explore the galaxy and search for other inhabitable planets. If we were to find another Earth-like planet for humans to inhabit, that would be when things get interesting. I think that in the time that it would take to develop faster-than-light space travel and explore the galaxy, the Earth would continue to be depleted of all of it's natural resources. At that point, the rich will be able to escape and the poor will be left behind to suffer the consequences of the many years of lavish lifestyles lived by the wealthy. It would be like something out of a sci-fi movie. And all that is not to mention what we might discover in the cosmos. On this Earth-like planet that we might find there would likely be unique life forms that have never existed on this Earth.

body: Hello how's it going Am I going to talk with a real person tonight or just myself for like 10 minutes? I have had a super busy day so far.  Finally getting a little bit of time to relax My dog is being a little crazy though so who knows if I'll actually get to relax. My sister-in-law actually got locked out of her place too so I had to give her a ride to and from work today since her car keys were inside. That was interesting Just got back from taking her home from work. She works for some soda shop here in Provo I'm just watching ESPN and relaxing.  Perks of getting all my homework done a day early I have a project and test this Friday though which I'll have to double down on tomorrow. Because Friday evening we are going to be going to a big party with my family so I'll have to have everything done before then. Okay, well.  It's been nice chatting with you chitchatter23 Responding to the prompt.  I don't think computers in general will ever be given the right to vote, however I do believe that certain Artificial Intelligences will be given that right. There is actually an AI that's a citizen of Saudi Arabia currently.  So certain countries do seem to think it's a real possibility that we will have citizens that are computer s one day Pretty cool stuff BYU has a couple of courses currently for CS students. One is about Artificial Intelligence and the other is Machine Learning.  Pretty neat stuff. There is also a research lab that does some AI ML projects such as chit chat.  I believe it's called the recognition and cognition lab I think it would be really cool to help out on a project such as this one. Just learning how the technology works and the basic architecture behind the programs would be really neat I have considered really diving in to that subject. It would be pretty neat.  But I'm a little unsure I think I like frontend development more than anything else right now. So like UI/UX stuff it's much more engaging and it's fun to be able to see a lot of your work actually materialize. I haven't taken 256 or 456 yet, but I'm going to take 256 next semester That's UI/UX in case you were wondering/ I think I am going to take 3 CS classes next semester. But probably just 2 and then one of the math requirements I still have linear algebra to take. So that will be interesting I'll probably just meet with an academic counselor to plan out my next couple of semesters. I'm watching friends now, and It's really remarkable how applicable like all of their references are to today as well. body: Good morning How are you doing today If I had a magic wand I would totally just make it so people can't talk when they are being mean or annoying Probably would also throw fireworks out of it all of the time. Also, assuming this wand is even more powerful than wands portrayed in harry potter and I could literally do anything with it, I would probably just stroll into a hospital and start curing any sick kids that are there I don't know if I would cure everyone though.. As sad as that is, if every old person that there is lived from every injury and illness than the US economy would collapse. Social Security already struggles because of people living to be too old. If even more lived and that age expectancy went up more it would just destroy future generations who are forced to care for them. Just some food for though. thought. I think the best solution to our social security woes is to at least in the short term raise the age of when people can access it by about 5 years.  Or, offer a super cheap subsidized health insurance plan for elderly and cut down how much social security they receive in exchange I know it stinks, but people do on some level need to be responsible for their own retirement.  I think that if you want to retire as soon as you're able to get social securit security just so you don't need to make money and can live off of that it just wrong. Also, I think that full time jobs regardless of what field they are in should be required by law to force employees to take out at least some kind of 401k and contribute a bare minimum amount to it. Because when people opt out of those sorts of benefits, it's not just hurting them, but it hurts the rest of us. It's like someone who is fully capable of getting a decent job, but refuses so that they can just get unemployment benefits from the government. It's just wrong.  Legally it's not, but its still just wrong. That's why I think it should be a law that people get independent, PRIVATE 401k's that the government is not involved with and not responsible for. At least start now so that we can resolve the social security issue at the very least by the time we are retired. Because the senate and those making the budget decisions only think short term.  Not even really past 10 years.  Most bills are purely band aids for the short term.  And being as they are only elected for short periods of time, they don't care about anything other than what makes them look good to get re-elected. And by forcing us to take out 401k's would probably just make everyone mad honestly. But it would be responsible and would help us in the long run It's either that or they need to make big cuts elsewhere which they aren't willing to do. That is another issue that I get annoyed with.  Media and society in general now a days blame everything on Millenials. Millenials killed American Cheese, Millenials won't buy homes Millenials are waiting to get married. The real issue is that they caused so many problems for us that we are left to clean up the mess and can't afford these things. gotta go!

body: Hey! Sweet Yo I had the sweetest time at the game last night! I got to go down onto the field for the entire first half of the game. We got tickets with my parents to see the game behind the end zone on the North side of the field But my dad's friend has these passes to go onto the field, so I went down for the first half with him and my dad went down for the second half It was awesome We got to just follow along the field as the ball went up and down We were like in the hawaii defense huddle just listening to their coach getting angry with them it was super cool We ended up getting home at around 12 though Winnie (my dog) was not happy about that she ended up playing till 1 in the morning So we ended up staying up too this morning we totally slept in on accident and missed all of church Our ward meets at 8 am which kind of stinks so we woke up around 10 and just missed it all So we just kind of took the morning slow and got ready for the day We drove up and through the alpine loop, which was snowing lots and then came to my in laws for dinner/ to do laundry Winnie ended up peeing on Michaela's lap because she was so nervous so that was lots of fun But now we are just chilling out and watching some football as my mother in law makes dinner Fun stuff I I've started a new project at work we are now building out some employee management apps for some clients that I'm helping with I have a good prompt to talk about: Do you think that alternative energies are effective and worth the investment? I personally would say yes Although currently it still does cost quite a bit to operate clean energy plants, the benefits long term are so much better first off, the supply never really dies down.  We will almost always have solar and wind and some of these other solutions that have been invented the trade off is though that coal and natural gas and oil are far cheaper for us to use However, they are limited in supply and they are awful for the enviroment If you can use clean energy for long enough then a lot of times you can get your money's worth out of it. Another thing I'd be curious about your take on is the new bill prop 2 here in utah I think it's very interesting I think it was good that some compromises were made though regarding how strict the bill will be Marijuana should be legal to people who need it medically, but the problem I see with it is that people will use really lame and often times faked illnesses to get access to i it I think the bill is good in that they limit who can produce and sell it.  But, I think that it still doesn't do enough to ensure that only those who are very sick can get access to it. I worry that our state will just be filled with people who claim that for "nerves" they need to have marijuana or some other lame made up illness That's the only drawback that this bill will have It just makes it too easy for people to get it. Another interesting topic is that of space travel And whether it's even worth it. I personally would say yes. If you look back on the space race and all the technologies that it brought, it has a huge benefit to society In more recent years we have learned how to land rockets and reuse them(looking at spacex) Been able to make them economical and send people as tourists into space and send more satellites out as well In addition to that, the possibilities with establishing colonies on the moon and mars are just incredible They've discovered ice on the moon and on mars so we know that we could get water from there We have also discovered that the resources necessary for making fuel are present on both the moon and mars This makes it possible not just to land on these planets, but also to leave and return from them If we can establish a colony on the moon then we can then do tests and refine technologies at an exponential speed currently the international space station conducts experiments in zero gravity all the time but having an established colony in a sterile enviroment would make it possible to do so much more. In addition to all of these technologies that we can discover and create there we could also mine the moon for it's resources I don't remember specifically which minerals the moon has, but I have read that there are minerals there that are  becoming scarce on earth and would be very valuable for us. We could mine these materials and ship them back to the states When we have these kinds of operations going on, it makes it possible to create jobs and work there This would allow for more people to go to the moon and businesses to go there as well. These possibilities allow for people to then colonize and have families there thus making a whole nation of it's own on the moon They would probably establish their own laws and govern themselves it could also serve as a base for launching more rockets throughout the galaxy With lower gravity it would require minimal effort to send a rocket off from the moons surface We could test out space elevators! and dock ships out of orbit There are so many possibilities I am really excited to see something like this happen So returning to my original point, I think it would totally be worth exploring space I think the possibilites combined with all the technology that comes with space exploration is totally worth it. I think a lot of Elon Musk and spacex when it comes to the future of our planet. People who are innovative and discovering these new technologies and on the forefront of discovery Autonomous cars are something that are especially intruiging to me Currently we have lots of traffic in our big cities.  Typically its because someone taps their brakes really hard and it causes a chain reaction that goes for miles With autonomous vehicles this wouldn't happne! happen they could communicate with each other and flow perfectly on interstates causes traffic to decrease Merge perfectly without causing other cars to brake They could eliminate the need for intersections because cars would be able to talk with each other perfectly and avoid hitting each other as they pass through And on top of all of this efficiency that they will bring, they would also eliminate millions of deaths per year When you think of it, cars are death trap s we get ourselves killed all the time by stupid human errors cause while driving Autonomous cars would avoid accidents and save millions of lives per year currently tesla has made some huge strides in both vehicle safety and autonomous vehicles Their cars are extremely safe to the point where cars can get absolutely totalled and people walk away unharmed And they already have developed cars with autonomous features, they're just fine tuning it and waiting for legislation allowing for it's full adopted use Another curious thought of mine is technology causing more harm or is it helping more to our future? This is why I think they'll be huge in the future! The car industry in recentry years has seen many new changes that have been revolutionizing the way we see trasnportation. The biggest technological advancement, arguably in my opinion would be that of autonomous vehicles. These are vehicles that drive themselves with no human interaction. Tesla has hit news recently with their accouncements that they will have fully autonomous vehicles running within the following yeras year that is, pending government approval and liscensing restrictions. But even with all this exciting technology, what effect is this going to have on America's future? Not only can autonomous vehicles help prevent fatalities, they can prevent billions of dollars in damages each year making america not only safer, but more economical. In 2015 i remember reading that for roughly every 100 million miles driven there are about 1.12 vehicle fatalities. This may not seem like alot, but considering that there are billions of miles driven in the states thats like tens of thousands of fatalities that we didn't need to have happe happen. Those were all a result of human error. They could have all been prevented with autonomous vehicles. Elon musk thinks that they can have autonomous vehicles that will eliminate these deaths completely I get that a lot of people are skeptical as to whether or not these vehicles are actually safe enough to put our trust in. Especially due to the softwareware malfunctions or lack of human control while driving. But, the fact that AV's will follow traffic laws every time without fail, they'll have updatable software to fix and bugs and they'll improve the quality of their thinking over time, it would be dumb to not accept them. They'll prevent accidents on our roads. Fortunately companies are working in coordination with state and federal governments to push through laws to ensure vehicle safety Both with traditional and autonomous vehicles When these vehicles hit the road in our cities they will help prevent not only the loss of life, but also prevent thousands of car crashes each year saving us billions of dollars in damages. These expenses are a huge burden that AV's can help eliminate. AV's can predict traffic patterns and keep up a constant speed to prevent bottlenecks and accidents on our highways. Time lost is money lost in most commuters worlds. Not only will improved traffic mean more time for the conveniences of work and life, but also more flexibility with work for many as well. Besides just reducing traffic, we could also increase speed limits without causing danger to anyone 2 hour commutes can turn into 30 minute rides instead On the flip side, you could argue that technology is not advanced enough to achieve these feats. The other advantage to AV's is that they can collect data on what is happening in their customers cars and use this to predict what it should do in various scenarios So someone who is driving a tesla themselves, if they brake and the car thinks it wouldn't have braked, they company can look at that scenario and the camera footage and see whether they need to tweak their algorithms to account for that given situation. AV's also have the capability to reduce the need for so many parking lots in cities. With AV's one could run a quick errand or go to a quick meeting and have the car drive around the block or even head home for the day to not have to pay for expensive parking or take up parking in the city. Imagine the possibilities for cities and the opportunites for growth if all of the sudden half of the garages we currently have are no longer necessary. Not only could cities save on teh expensive cost of parking garages, but they could use this extra space is busy cities to build another productive thing such as a park or a commercial office building Many cities and businesses make quite a bit of money on parking and rely on its profits to drive other trasnportation projects forward. However, the potential from other busineesses in these areas will bring them more profits and boost the economy in the city so it would probably still be a win for cities It's hard to imagine a real world application where this would even be possible, cars doing the driving for us. Imagine going to the airport for a business trip or maybe to visit relatives in a different state. I would imagine most people would park their car in an economy lot and leave it there for several days until they got back. not only that, but they are forced to wait 30-60 minutes for the transit from the airport, onto a shuttle and finally to their car. With AV's people will be able to drop themselves off right at the drop off lane at the airport, tell their car to go home to save on the cost of parking, and upon arrival back home they could have it come pick them up right at baggage claim. Not only could people save money, but the convenience of the ordeal will be extremely lucrative in an ever evolving society of innovators. Airports generally are forced to build on lots twice as big as the airports themsevles to accomodate for parking Once again we could save the money and build more productive things than parking in those areas AV's will make way for smaller roads which will decrese the need for large road budgets and save room in cities. Many US interstates can have up to as many as 5-7 lanes for transit going in both directions. These enormous interstates are meant to accommodate the heavy transit that many cities see around the country. While some owuld argue that we should have larger roads with more cars and AV's on the road. Because of their advanced driving abilities we will be able to move more traffic faster and reduce the road congestion. Traffic lanes could also be able to be way smaller due to the accuracy or AV's in keeping distance from surrounding vehicels. Many traffic lanes are fairly wide to compensate for human error, but with AV's we can save on the space in cities and tighten the lanes allowing for bike lanes, larger sidewalks to promote walking parks benches and trees too Cities can save on less road maintenance, a key issue currently in the US We could use this money elsewhere with less money coming in from traffic tickets and parking, this could help exponentially in compensating for the lack of revenue being generate to AV's AV's are going to revolutionize the way we see trasportation because they will provide greater convenience with commuting. Many parents often face the dilemma of how they will be able to take their kids to so many activities and also work to pay the bills. With AV's parents will be able to drive their kids to school while sitting at their desks working. Their cars can tak their kids for them with no worries of risk or injury. The possibilites are endless! Many would argue that these innovations will make us more distant and lazy though too After all we are becoming a super lazy country Lots of obesity, smart phones, less pressure to marry and commit to creating families, all of those factor in to being lazy AV's are already legal in a few states so we know that some states are ready for AV's to become a standardized thing. There have been several laws permitting their use in states across the us currently and many efforts are being made to legalize the use across the country Telsa is so confident that I remember them offering an option to prepay for their autonomous features to have the car preprogrammed for it Several other companies are also working on their own models and pushing to have them ready by 2020 to compete with tesla.
